standard_anchor(im_algebra2_unit5, im_lesson, "IM-Alg2-U5",
    "IM Algebra2 Unit 5: Exponential Functions and Equations. In this unit, students explore exponential and logarithmic functions. The unit begins with students recalling geometric sequences and drawing a connection to the growth or decay of values by a constant growth factor. This leads to expressing exponential relationships using functions of the form                , where is the value of the function when           and is the growth…").
standard_anchor(im_algebra2_unit6, im_lesson, "IM-Alg2-U6",
    "IM Algebra2 Unit 6: Transformations of Functions. In this unit, students consider functions as a whole and understand how they can be transformed to fit the needs of a situation, which is an aspect of modeling with mathematics. Prior to this unit, students have worked with a variety of function types, such as polynomial, radical, and exponential. Students will build on this work in a later unit to transform periodic functions.…").
standard_anchor(im_algebra2_unit7, im_lesson, "IM-Alg2-U7",
    "IM Algebra2 Unit 7: Trigonometric Functions. In this unit, students are introduced to trigonometric functions. This unit builds directly on the work of a previous unit by having students apply their knowledge of transformations to trigonometric functions and use these functions to model periodic situations. The unit begins with a deep study of the unit circle, as students study circular motion within familiar contexts. St…").
standard_anchor(im_algebra2_unit8, im_lesson, "IM-Alg2-U8",
    "IM Algebra2 Unit 8: Statistical Inferences. This unit focuses on some important uses of randomization in statistics. Initially, students consider three types of study (experimental, observational, and survey) as ways of collecting data. In each form of study, random selection of participants and assignment into any subgroups is important for being able to generalize findings to a larger population. Students notice that a…").

% ─ geometry ─
standard_anchor(im_geometry_unit1, im_lesson, "IM-HSG-U1",
    "IM Geometry Unit 1: Constructions and Rigid Transformations. This unit begins with constructions, continues to rigid transformations, and concludes with an introduction to proof writing. In grade 8, students determined the angle-preserving and length-preserving properties of rigid transformations experimentally, mostly with the help of a coordinate grid. Students have also previously studied the angle properties that they will prove in t…").
standard_anchor(im_geometry_unit2, im_lesson, "IM-HSG-U2",
    "IM Geometry Unit 2: Congruence. In this unit, students prove a variety of figures congruent. They start with segments (2 vertices), then triangles (3 vertices), and finally quadrilaterals (4 vertices). Before starting this unit, students are familiar with rigid transformations and congruence from a previous unit. The triangle congruence theorems in this unit lay the foundation for triangle similarity in a sub…").
standard_anchor(im_geometry_unit3, im_lesson, "IM-HSG-U3",
    "IM Geometry Unit 3: Similarity. In this unit, students explore similar figures as pairs of figures for which one can be taken onto the other through a sequence of rigid transformations and a dilation. The work of this unit expands upon students’ understanding of similarity, previously encountered in grade 8, and their work in an earlier unit on congruence. The unit begins with an exploration of dilation prope…").
standard_anchor(im_geometry_unit4, im_lesson, "IM-HSG-U4",
    "IM Geometry Unit 4: Right Triangle Trigonometry. In this unit students build an understanding of ratios in right triangles, which leads to naming cosine, sine, and tangent as trigonometric ratios. Prior to beginning this unit, students will have considerable familiarity with right triangles and similarity. They learned to identify right triangles in grade 4. Students studied the Pythagorean Theorem in grade 8, and used simila…").
standard_anchor(im_geometry_unit5, im_lesson, "IM-HSG-U5",
    "IM Geometry Unit 5: Solid Geometry. In this unit, students practice spatial visualization in three dimensions. They sketch cross-sections, study dilations, derive volume formulas, and apply their understandings to solve problems. In previous grades, students studied multiple aspects of solids. In grade 6, they started calculating surface areas and volumes of right rectangular prisms. They extended this understand…").
standard_anchor(im_geometry_unit6, im_lesson, "IM-HSG-U6",
    "IM Geometry Unit 6: Coordinate Geometry. Prior to beginning this unit, students will have spent most of the course studying geometric figures not described by coordinates. However, students have seen figures on the grid (notably transformations in grade 8) as well as lines and curves on the coordinate plane (in previous courses). This unit brings together students’ experience from previous years with their new underst…").
standard_anchor(im_geometry_unit7, im_lesson, "IM-HSG-U7",
    "IM Geometry Unit 7: Circles. In this unit, students investigate the geometry of circles more closely. In grade 7, students used formulas for the area and circumference of a circle to solve problems. Earlier in this course, students made formal geometric constructions, studied similarity and proportional reasoning, and proved theorems about lines and angles. This unit builds on these skills and concepts. In…").
standard_anchor(im_geometry_unit8, im_lesson, "IM-HSG-U8",
    "IM Geometry Unit 8: Conditional Probability. In this unit, students extend their understanding of probability, sample spaces, and events from their introduction in grade 7. The chance experiments under consideration have multiple parts, such as rolling a number cube and then flipping a coin—allowing events within the sample space to be considered in new ways. The unit begins with students creating different models for und…").

% ── Tier 2: lesson-level anchors (K-5) ──────────────
% ─ kindergarten ─
%   Unit 1
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u1_l1, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U1-L1",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 1 Lesson 1: Explore Connecting Cubes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to explore connecting cubes. Teachers also have an opportunity to gather formative assessment data about students’ counting concepts and skills. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the term “connecting cubes” refers to a tool used to do math. | Explore connecting cubes and describe (orally) the exploration.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u1_l2, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U1-L2",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 1 Lesson 2: Explore Pattern Blocks. The purpose of this lesson is for students to explore pattern blocks. Teachers also have an opportunity to gather formative assessment data about students’ counting concepts and skills. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the term “pattern blocks” refers to a tool used to do math. | Explore pattern blocks and describe (orally) the exploration.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u1_l3, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U1-L3",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 1 Lesson 3: Explore 2-Color Counters and 5-Frames. The purpose of this lesson is for students to explore two-color counters and 5-frames. Teachers also have an opportunity to gather formative assessment data about students’ counting concepts and skills. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the terms “counters” and “5-frame” refer to tools used to do math. | Explore counters and 5-frames and describe (orally) the exploration.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u1_l4, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U1-L4",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 1 Lesson 4: Explore Geoblocks. The purpose of this lesson is for students to explore geoblocks. Teachers also have an opportunity to gather formative assessment data about students’ counting concepts and skills. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the term “geoblocks” refers to a tool used to do math. | Explore geoblocks and describe (orally) the exploration.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u1_l5, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U1-L5",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 1 Lesson 5: Explore Math Tools. The purpose of this lesson is for students to explore math tools. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the term “math tool” refers to a thing that you use to help you do math. | Describe (orally) an object made with math tools.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u1_l6, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U1-L6",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 1 Lesson 6: Look for Small Groups. The purpose of this lesson is for students to recognize and name small groups of objects and images without counting. Goals: Describe (orally) the number of objects in an image within 4. | Use fingers to represent a group of images within 4.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u1_l7, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U1-L7",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 1 Lesson 7: Classroom Scavenger Hunt. The purpose of this lesson is for students to recognize and name small groups of objects and images without counting. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for determining the number of images or objects in a group. | Use fingers to represent groups of images or objects.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u1_l8, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U1-L8",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 1 Lesson 8: Different Groups, Same Quantity. The purpose of this lesson is for students to identify and match groups with the same number of objects or images without counting. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the phrase “the same number of” means there is a one-to-one correspondence between two groups. | Match (orally) groups of images that represent the same number of objects.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u1_l9, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U1-L9",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 1 Lesson 9: Create Picture Books. The purpose of this lesson is for students to recognize and represent groups of up to 4 objects and images without counting. Goals: Identify (orally) groups with a given number of objects. | Use drawings of objects to represent a given written number.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u1_l10, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U1-L10",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 1 Lesson 10: Are There Enough?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to develop and practice one-to-one correspondence in the context of answering \"are there enough?\" questions. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the question “are there enough?” means that it needs to be determined if there is one object in a group for every object in another group. | Determine (orally) whether there are enough in a given situation.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u1_l11, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U1-L11",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 1 Lesson 11: Get Enough. The purpose of this lesson is for students to develop and practice one-to-one correspondence as they make groups with enough objects. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for making groups with enough objects to match a given group of objects or images.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u1_l12, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U1-L12",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 1 Lesson 12: How Many Are There? (Part 1). The purpose of this lesson is for students to count collections of objects. The focus is saying one number for each object. Goals: Determine (orally) the number of objects within 10.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u1_l13, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U1-L13",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 1 Lesson 13: How Many Are There? (Part 2). The purpose of this lesson is for students to count collections of up to 10 objects. The focus is keeping track of which objects have been counted. Goals: Explain (orally) methods for keeping track of objects while counting.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u1_l14, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U1-L14",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 1 Lesson 14: Answer “How Many?” Questions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to count collections of up to 10 objects. The focus is understanding that the last number tells us how many objects there are (cardinality). Goals: Ask (orally) and answer “how many?” questions.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u1_l15, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U1-L15",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 1 Lesson 15: Explain How You Counted. The purpose of this lesson is for students to count collections of objects. The focus is for students to show and explain how they counted to a partner. Goals: Explain (orally) methods for counting a collection of objects.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u1_l16, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U1-L16",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 1 Lesson 16: Represent Our Collections. The purpose of this lesson is for students to count collections of objects. The focus is on students representing how they counted. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) methods for representing a collection of objects.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u1_l17, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U1-L17",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 1 Lesson 17: Model with Math Tools. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use math tools to create a model of objects in the classroom. Goals: Ask (orally) and answer “how many?” questions.").
%   Unit 2
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l1, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L1",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 1: Fingers as a Math Tool. The purpose of this lesson is for students to recognize, name, and show quantities with their fingers. Goals: Determine the number of fingers shown within 10 and express (orally) the quantity with the number name. | Use fingers to represent a given number within 10.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l2, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L2",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 2: Count and Arrange. The purpose of this lesson is for students to count objects and notice that changing the arrangement of a group of objects does not change the number of objects. Goals: Determine the number of objects in a group each time it is arranged in different ways. | Explain (orally) strategies for determining the number of objects in a collection.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l3, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L3",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 3: Groups That Look Very Different. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare groups of objects with very different quantities. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the meaning of terms “more”, “fewer”, and “less”. | Create a group with more or fewer objects than a given group.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l4, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L4",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 4: Groups That Look Alike. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare groups of objects that are close in quantity. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for comparing groups of objects within 10.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l5, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L5",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 5: Make Groups of More, Fewer, or the Same. The purpose of this lesson is for students to make groups that have more, fewer, or the same number of objects as another group. Goals: Use fingers to represent a number that is more than, fewer than, or the same as the number of fingers in an image. | Use “more than” and “fewer than” to compare (orally) groups of objects.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l6, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L6",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 6: Use “More,” “Fewer,” or “the Same Number” to Describe Groups. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use comparison language to describe the number of objects in groups. Goals: Use “more,” “fewer”, or “the same number” to compare (orally) groups of objects.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l7, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L7",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 7: Write Numbers 1–5. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice writing numbers. Goals: Write numbers 1–5.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l8, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L8",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 8: Write Numbers 6–10. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice writing numbers. Goals: Write numbers 6–10.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l9, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L9",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 9: Count Images in Different Arrangements. The purpose of this lesson is for students to count groups of up to 10 images and understand that the order in which the images are counted does not change the number of images. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for counting organized groups of images. | Identify (orally) and write numbers within 10.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l10, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L10",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 10: Compare Matching Images. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare groups of up to 10 images. Goals: Use “more” and “fewer” to compare (orally) groups of images.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l11, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L11",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 11: More, Fewer, or the Same. The purpose of this lesson is for students to identify groups that have more, less, or the same number as a given group of images. Goals: Determine (orally) groups that have the same number of images. | Explain (orally) strategies for comparing numbers represented with images in 5-frames.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l12, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L12",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 12: Find More, Fewer, or the Same. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare the number of images in groups and use “fewer,” “more,” and “the same number” to describe their relative size. Goals: Use “more,” “fewer,” and “the same number” to compare (orally) groups of images.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l13, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L13",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 13: Create Groups of Images. The purpose of this lesson is for students to create groups of images with more, fewer, or the same number of images as a given group. Goals: Draw groups that have “more” images, “fewer” images, and “the same number” of images as a given group. | Draw groups that match given comparison statements.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l14, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L14",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 14: Connect Quantities and Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to connect quantities to written and spoken numbers. Goals: Determine (orally) the number of objects in a group. | Identify (orally) and write numbers within 10.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l15, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L15",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 15: Numbers in Many Ways. The purpose of this lesson is for students to connect groups of images in different arrangements to spoken and written numbers. Goals: Determine (orally) the number of images presented in lines, arrays, and circles, on fingers, and on 5-frames. | Match (orally) written numbers and groups of images.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l16, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L16",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 16: Count Out Objects. The purpose of this lesson is for students to count out a given number of objects. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) different groups of objects that represent the same written number. | Create a group of objects to represent a given written number.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l17, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L17",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 17: Draw Groups of Things. The purpose of this lesson is for students to draw a given number of images. Goals: Draw groups to represent a given written number.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l18, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L18",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 18: Write Numbers to Represent Quantities. The purpose of this lesson is for students to write numbers to represent quantities. Goals: Determine the number of objects in a group and express (orally) the quantity using the number name. | Write a number to represent a group of objects.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l19, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L19",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 19: Order Towers and Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to order numbers from 1 to 10. Goals: Explain (orally) approaches for ordering numbers from 1 to 10.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l20, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L20",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 20: 1 More or 1 Less with Towers and Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to identify 1 more or 1 less than a given number. Goals: Identify and represent a number that is “one more” or “one less” than a given number.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l21, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L21",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 21: Compare Numbers and Images. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare groups of images and numbers 1‒10. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for comparing groups of images.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l22, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L22",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 22: Represent and Compare Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent and compare quantities and numbers 1 to 10. Goals: Represent the same number in multiple ways, including objects, drawings, and a written number. | Use “more,” “less,” or “the same number” to compare numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l23, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L23",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 23: Compare Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare numbers 1–10. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for comparing written numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u2_l24, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U2-L24",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 2 Lesson 24: Set the Table. The purpose of this lesson is for students to draw pictures and write numbers to represent quantities. Goals: Describe (orally) features of a representation that make it easier to interpret. | Interpret (orally) a representation of a real-world context.").
%   Unit 3
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u3_l1, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U3-L1",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 3 Lesson 1: What We Know about Shapes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use informal language to describe shapes and tell what they know about different shapes. Goals: Describe (orally) shapes in a picture, using informal language.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u3_l2, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U3-L2",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 3 Lesson 2: Match Shapes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to identify shapes that are the same. Goals: Identify (orally) simple shapes in a picture composed of many different shapes.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u3_l3, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U3-L3",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 3 Lesson 3: Describe and Compare Shapes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to describe and compare shapes. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) shapes.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u3_l4, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U3-L4",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 3 Lesson 4: Describe, Compare, and Sort Shapes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to describe, compare, and sort shapes. Goals: Describe (orally) attributes of shapes using informal language.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u3_l5, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U3-L5",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 3 Lesson 5: Circles and Triangles. The purpose of this lesson is for students to identify, describe, and compare circles and triangles. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for distinguishing between circles, triangles, and shapes that are not circles or triangles. | Write numbers to represent how many circles and triangles.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u3_l6, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U3-L6",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 3 Lesson 6: Rectangles and Squares. The purpose of this lesson is for students to identify, describe, and compare rectangles and squares. Goals: Describe (orally) features of rectangles and shapes that are not rectangles.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u3_l7, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U3-L7",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 3 Lesson 7: Build with Straws. The purpose of this lesson is for students to build shapes from components. Goals: Determine if straws are longer or shorter than a given line. | Use the terms “longer than” and “shorter than” to compare (orally) the lengths of two objects.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u3_l8, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U3-L8",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 3 Lesson 8: Draw Shapes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to draw shapes. Goals: Describe (orally) shapes. | Draw or create shapes based on a description.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u3_l9, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U3-L9",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 3 Lesson 9: Shapes Are Everywhere. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use what they know about shapes and their attributes to name and describe shapes in the environment. Goals: Create a representation of a triangle, a rectangle, or a circle in the environment. | Name (orally) triangles, rectangles, and circles in the environment.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u3_l10, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U3-L10",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 3 Lesson 10: Put Together Pattern Blocks. The purpose of this lesson is for students to put together shapes to form larger shapes. Goals: Create and describe (orally) shapes composed of smaller shapes.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u3_l11, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U3-L11",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 3 Lesson 11: Same Shapes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to identify shapes that are the same, regardless of orientation. Goals: Determine pattern blocks that are the same when presented in different orientations. | Explain (orally) how to determine if two pattern block shapes are the same.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u3_l12, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U3-L12",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 3 Lesson 12: More than 1 Way to Make a Shape. The purpose of this lesson is for students to put together shapes in multiple ways to form larger shapes. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) shapes composed of smaller shapes. | Create a given shape in different ways, using pattern blocks.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u3_l13, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U3-L13",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 3 Lesson 13: Describe and Match Shapes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use positional words to describe the location of pattern blocks in a larger shape. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the terms “above,” “below,” “next to,” and “behind” are used to describe the location of objects. | Describe (orally) the location of shapes, using “above,” “below,” “next to,” and “behind.”").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u3_l14, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U3-L14",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 3 Lesson 14: Shapes in Art. The purpose of this lesson is for students to put together shapes in a way that makes sense to them. Goals: Describe (orally) shapes in artwork. | Present (using other representations) artwork made from shapes.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u3_l15, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U3-L15",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 3 Lesson 15: Animal Shape Stamp Art. The purpose of this lesson is for students to put shapes together to represent objects in the real world. Goals: Create objects composed of smaller shapes and describe them (orally), using the names of the shapes and the words “more” and “fewer.”").
%   Unit 4
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u4_l1, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U4-L1",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 4 Lesson 1: Count 2 Groups of Objects. The purpose of this lesson is for students to count 2 groups of objects to find the total, within 10. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the phrase “how many altogether?” refers to the total number of objects given 2 groups of objects. | Determine the total number of objects, within 10, given 2 groups of objects, and express the total as a written number.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u4_l2, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U4-L2",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 4 Lesson 2: Count 2 Groups of Images. The purpose of this lesson is for students to count 2 groups of images to find the total within 10. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the term “add” refers to putting together 2 groups of objects. | Repeat (orally) statements of the form “_____ and _____ is _____” to represent addition statements.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u4_l3, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U4-L3",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 4 Lesson 3: Count 2 Groups of Scattered Images. The purpose of this lesson is for students to count to find the total number of images in 2 scattered groups. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the phrase “find the total” refers to a count of all the images given 2 groups of images. | Determine the total number of scattered images, given 2 groups of images, and express the total as a written number.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u4_l4, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U4-L4",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 4 Lesson 4: Add with Objects. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use objects to show the action of addition. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the term “count out” refers to making a group with a given number of objects. | Generalize (orally) that the phrase “add _____ more” means put that many more objects or images in a given group. | Use objects to represent adding on to an existing gr").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u4_l5, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U4-L5",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 4 Lesson 5: Subtract with Objects. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent the action of subtraction with objects. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the term “subtract” refers to taking away. | Repeat (orally) statements in the form “_____ take away _____ . There are _____ left.” to represent subtraction statements. | Represent and solve subtraction problems.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u4_l6, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U4-L6",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 4 Lesson 6: Tell and Act Out Stories. The purpose of this lesson is for students to tell and act out addition and subtraction stories. Goals: Describe (orally) a math story about a picture. | Represent an Add To or Take From story problem by acting it out.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u4_l7, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U4-L7",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 4 Lesson 7: Use Objects to Represent Stories. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use objects to demonstrate the actions of addition and subtraction in stories. Goals: Create (orally) Add To and Take From stories. | Represent an Add To or Take From story problem using words and objects.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u4_l8, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U4-L8",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 4 Lesson 8: Represent and Solve Story Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent and solve story problems in a way that makes sense to them. Goals: Represent and solve an Add To, Result Unknown problem.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u4_l9, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U4-L9",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 4 Lesson 9: Solve Story Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve story problems in a way that makes sense to them and to understand how objects and drawings represent a story problem. Goals: Comprehend the notation “0” represents no objects.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u4_l10, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U4-L10",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 4 Lesson 10: Compare Drawings. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare drawings that represent story problems. Goals: Interpret (orally) drawings that represent an Add To, Result Unknown problem.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u4_l11, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U4-L11",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 4 Lesson 11: Drawings to Represent Story Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to draw a picture to represent and solve a story problem. Goals: Present (using other representations) a drawing for representing a Take From, Result Unknown problem.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u4_l12, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U4-L12",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 4 Lesson 12: Compare Addition and Subtraction Story Problems. The purpose of this lesson is to solve and compare Add To, Result Unknown and Take From, Result Unknown story problems. Goals: Comprehend the notation “A + B” can be used to represent an Add To problem and is read as “A plus B.” | Comprehend the notation “A – B” can be used to represent a Take From problem and is read as “A minus B.” | Represent and solve an Add To, Result Unknown problem.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u4_l13, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U4-L13",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 4 Lesson 13: Create Story Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to create an addition or subtraction story problem. Goals: Create (orally) Add To, Result Unknown and Take From, Result Unknown problems that represent a picture. | Determine whether a story problem shows adding to (addition) or taking from (subtraction).").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u4_l14, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U4-L14",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 4 Lesson 14: Expressions and Story Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to connect expressions to story problems. Goals: Interpret (orally) a subtraction expression that represents a Take From, Result Unknown problem. | Match (orally) expressions and Add To or Take, From, Result Unknown problems.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u4_l15, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U4-L15",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 4 Lesson 15: Expressions and Drawings. The purpose of this lesson is for students to connect expressions to drawings. Goals: Create expressions that represent images and images that represent expressions. | Match (orally) expressions and images that represent the same addition or subtraction relationships.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u4_l16, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U4-L16",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 4 Lesson 16: Find the Value of Expressions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find the value of addition and subtraction expressions in a way that makes sense to them. Goals: Explain (orally) methods for finding the value of addition and subtraction expressions.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u4_l17, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U4-L17",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 4 Lesson 17: Add 0 and 1. The purpose of this lesson is for students to notice patterns when 0 and 1 are added to a number. Goals: Generalize (orally) that adding 0 results in the same number. | Generalize (orally) that adding 1 results in the next number in the count sequence.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u4_l18, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U4-L18",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 4 Lesson 18: Tell Story Problems for Expressions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to consider the information needed to solve story problems and to create a story problem to match an expression. Goals: Create an expression and a story problem that represent the same relationships.").
%   Unit 5
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u5_l1, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U5-L1",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 5 Lesson 1: Make 2 Parts. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compose and decompose numbers up to 9 and understand that numbers can be composed and decomposed in more than one way. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the term “part” refers to a portion of a total collection. | Use objects to compose or decompose a number within 9.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u5_l2, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U5-L2",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 5 Lesson 2: Make and Break Apart Pattern Block Designs. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compose and decompose numbers up to 9 in more than 1 way. Goals: Create designs composed of 2 types of pattern blocks. Describe (orally) this composition using number names for each part and the total.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u5_l3, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U5-L3",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 5 Lesson 3: Snap the Cubes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find multiple decompositions of a number and look for patterns in decompositions. Goals: Describe (orally) a cube tower with two parts using number names for each part and the total. Represent it with a drawing.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u5_l4, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U5-L4",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 5 Lesson 4: Find All the Ways. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find all the ways to decompose a number. Goals: Create an object with two parts that represents an equation. | Represent the 2 parts and total of a given image with an equation.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u5_l5, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U5-L5",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 5 Lesson 5: Put Together. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve Put Together, Total Unknown story problems. Goals: Explain (orally) methods for solving a Put Together, Total Unknown problem, within 10.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u5_l6, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U5-L6",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 5 Lesson 6: Red and Yellow Apples. The purpose of this lesson is for students to make sense of Put Together/Take Apart, Both Addends Unknown story problems. Goals: Describe (orally) the known and unknown quantities in a Put Together, Total Unknown problem and a Put Together/Take Apart, Both Addends Unknown story.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u5_l7, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U5-L7",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 5 Lesson 7: Solve Both Addends In Unknown Story Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve Put Together/Take Apart, Both Addends Unknown story problems in a way that makes sense to them. Goals: Solve a Put Together/Take Apart, Both Addends Unknown problem.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u5_l8, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U5-L8",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 5 Lesson 8: More than One Way. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find more than one solution to a Put Together/Take Apart, Both Addends Unknown story problem. Goals: Interpret (orally) drawings that represent a solution to a Put Together/Take Apart, Both Addends Unknown problem. | Present (using words and other representations) a strategy for solving a Put Together/Take Apart, Both Addends Unknown problem.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u5_l9, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U5-L9",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 5 Lesson 9: Story Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve addition and subtraction story problems. Goals: Match (orally) story problems and drawings that represent the same addition or subtraction relationships. | Solve a Take From, Result Unknown and Put Together/Take Apart, Both Addends Unknown problems and represent the solution with an expression.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u5_l10, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U5-L10",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 5 Lesson 10: Introduce the 10-Frame. The purpose of this lesson is for students to understand the 10-frame as 2 combined 5-frames and to relate the 10-frame to fingers on two hands. Goals: Comprehend the term “10-frame” (in spoken language) refers to a tool made of two 5-frames put together that is used to represent numbers up to 10. | Use counters and 10-frames to represent numbers within 10.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u5_l11, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U5-L11",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 5 Lesson 11: Equations That Show 10. The purpose of this lesson is for students to connect equations with compositions and decompositions of 10 on 10-frames and fingers. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the term “equation” refers to the notation “C = A + B”, is used to represent an addition situation, and is read as “C is A plus B.” | Match (orally) equations and images that represent the same compositions and decompositions of 10.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u5_l12, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U5-L12",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 5 Lesson 12: How Many Are Missing?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compose and decompose 10 in multiple ways and find the number that makes 10 when added to a given number. Goals: Determine the number that makes 10 when added to a given number. | Match (orally) equations and counters on 10-frames that represent the same compositions and decompositions of 10.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u5_l13, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U5-L13",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 5 Lesson 13: Make 10. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find the number that makes 10 when added to a given number. Goals: Create equations that represent decompositions of 10. | Determine (orally) the number that makes 10 when added to a given number.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u5_l14, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U5-L14",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 5 Lesson 14: Towers of 10. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice finding the number that makes 10 when added to a given number. Goals: Explain (orally) methods for determining the number of objects that makes 10 when added to a given number of objects. | Match (orally) cubes and counters on a 10-frame that represent the same decomposition of 10.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u5_l15, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U5-L15",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 5 Lesson 15: Packing Up Fruit. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compose and decompose numbers to 10 and represent situations involving compositions and decompositions of numbers to 10. Goals: Present (orally and using other representations) compositions and decompositions within 10 that represents a solution to a real-world context.").
%   Unit 6
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u6_l1, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U6-L1",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 6 Lesson 1: Count Larger Collections of Objects. The purpose of this lesson is for students to count to answer “how many?” questions about groups of up to 20 objects. Goals: Determine the number of objects within 20.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u6_l2, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U6-L2",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 6 Lesson 2: Keep Track of Objects. The purpose of this lesson is for students to keep track of objects that have been counted in order to accurately count groups of up to 20 objects. Goals: Explain (orally) methods for keeping track of objects while counting collections up to 20.").
standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u6_l3, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U6-L3",
