standard_anchor(im_kindergarten_u8_l21, im_lesson, "IM-GK-U8-L21",
    "IM Kindergarten Unit 8 Lesson 21: Make and Break Apart Numbers 11–19. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compose and decompose numbers 11–19, using 10 ones and some more ones. Goals: Choose strategies for decomposing numbers 11–19 into a group of 10 and some more; and express the decomposition with an equation.").
% ─ grade1 ─
%   Unit 1
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u1_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U1-L1",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 1 Lesson 1: Count and Add. The purpose of this lesson is for students to count objects and relate counting to addition. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for organizing and counting collections of objects.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u1_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U1-L2",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 1 Lesson 2: Explore Expressions and Sums. The purpose of this lesson is to write addition expressions within 10 and find the sums. Goals: Comprehend (in written and spoken language) the phrase “value of a sum” refers to the total when adding two or more numbers. | Represent sums with expressions and find the value of sums within 10.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u1_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U1-L3",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 1 Lesson 3: Add 1 or 2. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add within 10 when one addend is 1 or 2. Goals: Find the value of sums within 10 when one addend is 1 or 2.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u1_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U1-L4",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 1 Lesson 4: More Work with 1 and 2. The purpose of this lesson is for students to subtract 1 or 2 within 10. Goals: Find the value of differences within 10 when 1 or 2 is subtracted.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u1_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U1-L5",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 1 Lesson 5: Explore Addition and Subtraction. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add and subtract within 10. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the phrase “value of a difference” refers to the result when one number is subtracted from another. | Represent differences with expressions and find the value of differences within 10.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u1_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U1-L6",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 1 Lesson 6: Center Day 1. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice adding and subtracting within 10. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for finding the number that makes 10 when added to a given number.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u1_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U1-L7",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 1 Lesson 7: Sort Math Tools. The purpose of this lesson is for students to sort objects into categories and tell how many objects are in each category. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the meaning of the term “category.” | Describe (orally) the categories chosen for sorting objects and determine (orally) the number of objects in each category.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u1_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U1-L8",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 1 Lesson 8: Sort and Count Shape Cards. The purpose of this lesson is for students to sort shapes and create a representation that shows the number of shapes in each category. Goals: Describe (orally) the categories chosen for sorting shapes and determine the number of shapes in each category. | Present (using words and other representations) an approach for representing the number of shapes in 3 categories.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u1_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U1-L9",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 1 Lesson 9: Which Is Your Favorite?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to collect categorical data about the class, organize it, and represent it in a way others can understand. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the meaning of the terms “survey” and “data.” | Organize and represent data. | Represent categorical data and compare and contrast (orally) different approaches for representing the same categorical data.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u1_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U1-L10",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 1 Lesson 10: Center Day 2. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add and subtract within 10. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for finding the number that makes 10 when added to a given number.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u1_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U1-L11",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 1 Lesson 11: Class Pet Surveys. The purpose of this lesson is for students to write and evaluate statements based on data in a visual representation. Goals: Explain (orally) how to determine if a statement about data is true or false. | Interpret (orally and in writing) data represented with tally marks in a table.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u1_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U1-L12",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 1 Lesson 12: How Many?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to answer “how many in each category?” and “how many in all?” questions about data and explain their thinking. Goals: Answer (orally) “how many in each category” and “how many in all” questions about data represented in tables.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u1_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U1-L13",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 1 Lesson 13: Questions about Data. The purpose of this lesson is for students to ask questions about data that can be answered by a given data representation. Goals: Ask (orally) and answer questions that can be answered about data represented in a table. | Explain (orally) how to determine if a question about data can be answered using a given representation.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u1_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U1-L14",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 1 Lesson 14: Center Day 3. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice working with data and adding and subtracting within 10. Goals: Represent a collection of sorted shapes. Ask (orally) questions that can be answered about the quantities in the representation.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u1_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U1-L15",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 1 Lesson 15: Free-Time Activities. The purpose of this lesson is for students to create a survey and collect, represent, and interpret the data. Goals: Create and describe (orally) a representation of collected data. | Explain (orally) how data was used to make a recommendation in a real-world context.").
%   Unit 2
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L1",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 1: Represent Story Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent and solve Add To and Take From, Result Unknown story problems in a way that makes sense to them. Goals: Represent the actions of Add To and Take From, Result Unknown problems in different ways.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L2",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 2: Solve Story Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare the different ways they add or subtract to solve Add To and Take From, Result Unknown story problems. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) strategies for representing and solving story problems, including counting strategies. | Explain (orally) strategies for solving Add To and Take From, Result Unknown problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L3",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 3: A Change Is Coming. The purpose of this lesson is for students to make sense of and solve a new type of problem—Add To, Change Unknown. Students solve the problems in a way that makes sense to them and identify the answer to a story problem in their work. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) Add To story problems with an unknown total or an unknown addend. | Explain (orally) strategies for solving Add To, Change Unknown problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L4",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 4: A Change Unknown. The purpose of this lesson is for students to interpret a strategy for solving an Add To, Change Unknown problem that involves using drawings to count on. Students use strategies that make sense to them to determine the number that makes an Goals: Comprehend the notation “       ” can be used to represent an unknown in an equation. | Explain (orally) strategies for finding the value of an unknown addend, including counting on.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L5",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 5: Center Day 1. The purpose of this lesson is for students to tell and solve story problems, and add and subtract within 10. Goals: Create (orally) and solve story problems involving addition and subtraction.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L6",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 6: Problems about Pets. The purpose of this lesson is for students to revisit the structure of Put Together/Take Apart, Total Unknown problems and to compare different ways to represent and solve them. Goals: Interpret (orally) expressions that represent the same story problem. | Represent and solve Put Together/Take Apart, Total Unknown problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L7",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 7: One Part Red, One Part Yellow. The purpose of this lesson is for students to make sense of and represent different part-part-whole relationships in the context of Put Together/Take Apart situations. Students write expressions, make sense of equations, and describe what t Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving Put Together/ Take Apart, Both Addends Unknown problems. | Represent Put Together/Take Apart problems with expressions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L8",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 8: One Part Red, How Many Yellow?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent and solve Put Together/Take Apart, Addend Unknown story problems. Goals: Represent and solve Put Together/Take Apart, Addend Unknown problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L9",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 9: What Is the Unknown?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent and solve different Put Together/Take Apart problems. Students compare different strategies for determining an unknown addend and make sense of the relationship between addition and su Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) addition and subtraction methods that represent ways to find an unknown addend. | Solve Put Together/Take Apart problems when the total, one addend, or both addends are unknown.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L10",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 10: Center Day 2. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice adding and subtracting within 10. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding within 10.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L11",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 11: Are There Enough?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent and solve “are there enough?” problems in a way that makes sense to them and use “1 more” or “1 fewer” to compare objects. Goals: Describe (orally) the difference between a larger quantity and a smaller quantity using “1 more” or “1 fewer.” | Explain (orally) methods for representing an “are there enough?” problem.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L12",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 12: How Many More? How Many Fewer?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve Compare, Difference Unknown story problems in a way that makes sense to them. Goals: Comprehend (orally and in writing) the “difference” between quantities refers to the answer to “how many more?” or “how many fewer?” | Describe (orally) the quantities in Compare, Difference Unknown problems and solve the problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L13",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 13: Compare Data. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve Compare, Difference Unknown story problems in a data context. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving Compare, Difference Unknown problems within a data context. | Interpret (orally) Compare, Difference Unknown problems as unknown addend problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L14",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 14: Compare with Addition or Subtraction. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve Compare, Difference Unknown story problems and deepen their understanding of subtraction as an unknown addend problem. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) different strategies for determining an unknown difference.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L15",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 15: Different Types of Story Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve a variety of story problems and discuss the relationship between subtraction and unknown addend problems. Goals: Represent and solve Put Together/Take Apart and Compare, Difference Unknown problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L16",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 16: Center Day 3. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice adding and subtracting within 10. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding and subtracting within 10.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l17, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L17",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 17: Equations with Unknowns. The purpose of this lesson is for students to interpret equations with a symbol for the unknown and match them to story problems. Goals: Match (orally) Add To, Take From, and Put Together/ Take Apart problems and equations.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l18, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L18",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 18: Addition and Subtraction Equations. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve Compare, Difference Unknown story problems and match addition and subtraction equations to the problems. Goals: Interpret (orally) addition equations with an unknown addend and subtraction equations that represent the same story problem. | Match (using words or other representations) Compare and Put Together/Take Apart, Addend Unknown problems and equations.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l19, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L19",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 19: How Do the Stories Compare?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare and solve story problems of different types they have seen throughout the unit. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) different story problems. | Represent story problems with equations and solve the problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l20, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L20",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 20: Story Problems and Equations. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent and solve story problems that involve an unknown addend. Goals: Ask (orally and in writing) questions to create story problems. | Create equations that can be used to represent or solve story problems. | Represent and solve a variety of story problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l21, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L21",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 21: Make Sense of Equations. The purpose of this lesson is for students to write equations and explain how they know an equation is true. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for finding the number that makes an equation true. | Represent Put Together/Take Apart situations with equations.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l22, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L22",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 22: Center Day 4. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice adding and subtracting within 10. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) equations used to represent and solve story problems. | Represent an equation by creating (orally) a story problem.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u2_l23, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U2-L23",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 2 Lesson 23: Story Problem Information. The purpose of this lesson is for students to analyze story problems that give too much or too little information. Goals: Determine (orally) if a story problem does not have enough information to solve the problem or if it has more than enough information to solve the problem.").
%   Unit 3
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L1",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 1: Sums I Know. The purpose of this lesson is for students to identify which sums within 10 they know and which they are still working on. Goals: Comprehend (in written and spoken language) the term “sum” can refer to an addition expression. | Identify the value of sums within 10 and explain (orally) strategies for finding the value of sums that are more challenging.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L2",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 2: Relate Counting to Addition. The purpose of this lesson is for students to understand and apply counting on and the commutative property in order to find sums within 10. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies used to add within 10, including counting strategies and using the commutative property (informally).").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L3",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 3: Are They Equal?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to identify expressions that have the same value. Goals: Explain (orally) how to determine whether or not equations with expressions on both sides of the equal sign are true.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L4",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 4: Sums of 10. The purpose of this lesson is to build toward fluency within 10 by looking for and making use of patterns in sums that have a value of 10. Goals: Create sums that have a value of 10 and explain (orally) strategies for finding all of the possible sums of 10.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L5",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 5: Find the Difference. The purpose of this lesson is for students to develop fluency with subtraction within 10, using the relationship between addition and subtraction. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for subtracting within 10, including those based on using known sums or differences. | Interpret (orally and using other representations) subtraction strategies based on the relationship between addition and subtraction.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L6",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 6: Story Problems within 10. The purpose of this lesson is to introduce students to a new type of story problem, Add To, Start Unknown. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving Add To and Take From problems, including Add To, Start Unknown problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L7",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 7: Center Day 1. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice adding within 10. Goals: Find and compare (orally) the values of sums and differences within 10.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L8",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 8: Ten as a Unit. The purpose of this lesson is for students to understand that 10 ones make a unit called a ten. Students compose and decompose teen numbers with a ten and some ones. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the term “ten” refers to a group of 10 ones. | Represent teen numbers as 1 ten and some ones.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L9",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 9: Addition with a Ten. The purpose of this lesson is for students to deepen their understanding that teen numbers are composed of a ten and some ones, and to find the value that makes an addition equation true when one addend is 10. Goals: Comprehend (orally) the term “teen number” refers to a number with one ten and between one and nine ones. | Find the number that makes an addition equation true, where one addend is 10. | Represent teen numbers with 10-frames, 2-digit numbers, and equations.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L10",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 10: Addition and Subtraction with a Ten. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find the value that makes an equation true when one value is a teen number and one is a ten. Goals: Interpret (orally) and use strategies for finding the number that makes a subtraction equation true based on the relationship between addition and subtraction. | Represent and solve Add To, Start Unknown and Add To, Change Unknown problems where the total is a teen number.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L11",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 11: Add to a Teen Number. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add within 20 when one addend is a teen number. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving an Add To, Result Unknown problem when one addend is a teen number. | Find the value of sums within 20 when one addend is a teen number.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L12",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 12: Subtract from a Teen Number. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add and subtract within 20 without composing or decomposing a ten. Goals: Explain (orally and with words or other representations) strategies for finding the number that makes addition and subtraction equations within 20 true. | Explain (orally) strategies for solving a Take From, Result Unknown problem where a one-digit number is subtracted from a tee").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L13",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 13: More Story Problems with Teen Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve Take From, Result or Change Unknown story problems. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving Take From, Change Unknown and Take From, Result Unknown problems when the total is a teen number.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L14",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 14: Center Day 2. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice adding and subtracting within 20. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for finding the number that makes an equation true.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L15",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 15: Solve Story Problems with Three Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve story problems with three addends, two of which make a ten, in a way that makes sense to them. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving story problems within 20 with three addends where two addends make a ten.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L16",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 16: Add 3 Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply the commutative and associative properties in order to make a ten when adding three numbers within 20, and make sense of equations with addition expressions on both sides of the equal sign Goals: Determine (orally and using words or other representations) if an expression with three addends has the same value as an expression with 10 as an addend. | Explain (orally) how to use a make a ten strategy to express an equation with three addends as an equation with two addends.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l17, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L17",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 17: Make 10 to Add. The purpose of this lesson is for students to look for and use patterns to add within 20. Students see that they can decompose one addend in order to make a ten. Goals: Describe (orally) patterns when adding one-digit numbers to 9. | Explain (orally) strategies for solving Put Together, Total Unknown problems within 20 that involve making a ten.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l18, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L18",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 18: Patterns in Addition. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find expressions equivalent to       expressions. Students then look for patterns in the expressions. Goals: Match (orally) expressions where 10 is an addend and other expressions that represent the same value. Describe (orally) patterns in the addends.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l19, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L19",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 19: Methods for Addition within 20. The purpose of this lesson is for students to analyze addition methods for adding within 20, then use those methods flexibly to find sums based on the numbers in a given expression. Goals: Explain (orally and using words or other representations) strategies for adding within 20. | Interpret (orally and using words or other representations) strategies for adding within 20, including those based on properties of operations and creating equivalent but easier or known").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l20, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L20",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 20: A Trip to the Zoo. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve story problems with three addends. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving Put Together/ Take Apart, Total Unknown problems with three addends.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l21, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L21",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 21: Center Day 3. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice adding within 20. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding 2 and 3 addends within 20.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l22, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L22",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 22: Subtract from Teen Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to subtract from a teen number. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for finding the value of differences with teen numbers. | Explain (using words or other representations) a strategy for solving a Take From, Result Unknown problem within 20.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l23, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L23",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 23: Use a Ten to Subtract. The purpose of this lesson is for students to notice how the unit of ten can be used to find differences within 20. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for subtraction, including those based on reasoning about a ten. | Interpret (orally) strategies based on subtracting from a ten or subtracting to get to 10.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l24, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L24",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 24: Relate Counting to Addition and Subtraction. The purpose of this lesson is for students to analyze and use counting on and taking away methods to subtract within 20. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for finding the number that makes addition and subtraction equations true. | Explain (orally) the subtraction strategies that take away and those that count on.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l25, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L25",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 25: How Do You Want to Subtract?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use subtraction methods flexibly to find differences. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving Add To and Take From story problems within 20. | Explain (orally) strategies for subtracting and how a strategy was chosen based on the numbers in the expression.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l26, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L26",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 26: What’s the Story?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve addition and subtraction story problems with the unknowns in all positions. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving Add To, Change Unknown and Take From, Change Unknown problems. | Present (using words or other representations) strategies for solving Add to and Take From story problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l27, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L27",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 27: Center Day 4. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice adding and subtracting within 20. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding and subtracting within 20 and compare the value of expressions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u3_l28, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U3-L28",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 3 Lesson 28: The Garden. The purpose of this lesson is for students to ask questions about a real-world situation that can be answered using mathematics. Goals: Ask (orally and in writing) questions about a real- world situation and identify which questions can be answered with addition or subtraction. | Create (in writing) and solve story problems that involve addition or subtraction within 20.").
%   Unit 4
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L1",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 1: Count Large Collections. The purpose of this lesson is for students to count groups of multiples of 10 objects in a way that makes sense to them. Goals: Represent strategies for organizing and counting collections of up to 60 objects (multiples of 10).").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L2",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 2: Match Representations of Tens. The purpose of this lesson is for students to interpret different base-ten representations of multiples of 10. Goals: Match (orally) different base-ten representations that represent the same multiples of 10.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L3",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 3: Addition and Subtraction with Tens. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add and subtract 10 from multiples of 10. Goals: Describe (orally) patterns when adding and subtracting 10 from multiples of 10. | Explain (orally) methods for adding and subtracting 10 from multiples of 10.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L4",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 4: More Addition and Subtraction with Tens. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add and subtract multiples of 10 from multiples of 10. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding and subtracting multiples of 10 from multiples of 10.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L5",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 5: Center Day 1. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice adding and subtracting a multiple of 10 from a multiple of 10. Students also practice adding and subtracting within 20. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding and subtracting multiples of 10.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L6",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 6: Count Larger Collections. The purpose of this lesson is for students to organize, count, and represent a group of objects. Goals: Interpret (orally and in writing) connecting cubes in towers of 10 that represent a number within 60. | Represent (orally) strategies for organizing and counting collections of objects up to 60 (not multiples of 10).").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L7",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 7: Numbers with Tens and Ones. The purpose of this lesson is for students to understand that two-digit numbers are composed of tens and ones. Goals: Create two-digit numbers and represent them with connecting cubes, base-ten diagrams, and as a number of tens and ones. | Generalize (orally) that the digit on the left of a “two- digit number” represents the number of tens and the digit on the right represents the number of ones").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L8",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 8: Different Representations of Tens and Ones. The purpose of this lesson is for students to interpret base-ten representations of two-digit numbers. Goals: Interpret (orally and using other representations) different base-ten representations of two-digit numbers (drawings, words, and expressions).").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L9",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 9: Show Me Your Number. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent the base-ten structure of two-digit numbers with drawings, words, and addition expressions that show the value of the tens and ones. Goals: Represent the same two-digit number in different ways, including connecting cubes, base-ten drawings, words, and addition expressions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L10",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 10: Write 2-Digit Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to write numbers to represent different base-ten representations including base-ten diagrams, _____ tens _____ ones, and expressions that show the value of the tens and ones digits. Goals: Create a two-digit number that represents a given base-ten representation.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L11",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 11: Add Tens to 2-Digit Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add a two-digit number and a multiple of 10. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding two-digit numbers and a multiple of 10. | Find the digit that makes an equation representing adding two-digit numbers and a multiple of 10 true.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L12",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 12: Mentally Add and Subtract Tens. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use base-ten understanding to mentally determine 10 more or 10 less than a two-digit number. Goals: Describe (orally) patterns in two-digit numbers when adding or subtracting 10.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L13",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 13: Center Day 2. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add and subtract within 20 and work with two-digit numbers. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding and subtracting within 20, including making a 10.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L14",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 14: Let’s Compare. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare two-digit numbers based on the value of the tens and ones digits. Students use “greater than” and “less than” to describe these comparisons. Goals: Comprehend (in written and spoken language) the meaning of the phrases “greater than” and “less than.” | Interpret (orally and using other representations) strategies for comparing two-digit numbers based on place value.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L15",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 15: Greater Than, Less Than. The purpose of this lesson is for students to learn the meaning of the symbols < and >. Students interpret comparison statements that use these symbols and the equal sign. Goals: Comprehend the meaning of the notation > and <. | Explain (orally) how to determine if a comparison statement is true. | Interpret (orally) comparison statements that use >, <, and =.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L16",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 16: Write Comparisons with Symbols. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare numbers based on the value of the tens and ones digits. Students also read and write comparisons using , , or . Goals: Create comparison statements with <, >, or = to compare 2 two-digit numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l17, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L17",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 17: Compare and Order Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare and order numbers based on the value of the tens and ones digits. Goals: Explain (orally) methods for ordering two-digit numbers from least to greatest.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l18, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L18",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 18: Center Day 3. The purpose of this lesson is for students to count, compare, and write two-digit numbers. Goals: Use place value understanding to create and order two-digit numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l19, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L19",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 19: Make 2-Digit Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent a two-digit number in more than one way, using tens and ones. Goals: Represent (using words or other representations) a two-digit number using different combinations of tens and ones.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l20, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L20",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 20: Make 2-Digit Numbers in Different Ways. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent two-digit numbers in different ways and identify two-digit numbers represented with different amounts of tens and ones. Goals: Create (using words and other representations) different combinations of tens and ones that represent the same two-digit number within 100. | Identify (orally and in writing) two-digit numbers that are represented as different combinations of tens and ones.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l21, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L21",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 21: Compare 2-Digit Numbers Shown in Different Ways. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare two-digit numbers that are represented in different ways. Goals: Explain (orally) methods for comparing two-digit numbers represented in different ways.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l22, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L22",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 22: Center Day 4. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use place value understanding to compare and write numbers. Goals: Describe (orally) and identify two-digit numbers using clues based on place value.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u4_l23, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U4-L23",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 4 Lesson 23: What Happens When You Estimate?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to consider the magnitude of numbers to 99 by estimating and consider situations to determine when counting to find an exact amount might be necessary. Goals: Explain (orally) how to decide if an estimate would be helpful when considering real-world contexts. | Explain (orally) strategies for estimating the number of objects presented in images.").
%   Unit 5
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u5_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U5-L1",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 5 Lesson 1: Add Tens or Ones. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add tens or ones to two-digit numbers, without composing a ten, in a way that makes sense to them. Goals: Explain (orally and using words or other representations) strategies for adding tens or ones to two-digit numbers, without composing a ten.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u5_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U5-L2",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 5 Lesson 2: How Did You Add?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add 2 two-digit numbers, without composing a ten, using methods based on place value and make sense of equations that represent addition methods. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding 2 two-digit numbers, without composing a ten. | Match (orally) equations and base-ten drawings that represent the same addition strategies.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u5_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U5-L3",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 5 Lesson 3: Add It, Explain It. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add 2 two-digit numbers, without composing a ten, using methods based on place value and to write equations to represent addition methods. Goals: Interpret (using words or other representations) equations that represent steps for adding based on place value. | Represent strategies for adding 2 two-digit numbers with equations and explain (orally and using words or other representations) the strategies.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u5_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U5-L4",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 5 Lesson 4: Center Day 1. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice adding within 100 without composing a ten. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for finding the number that makes equations with two-digit numbers true.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u5_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U5-L5",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 5 Lesson 5: Make a Ten. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add a two-digit number and a one-digit number within 100, with composing a ten, in a way that makes sense to them. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding a one-digit number and a two-digit a number that include composing a ten.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u5_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U5-L6",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 5 Lesson 6: Make a Ten and Make Sense of Equations. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add one-digit and two-digit numbers, with composing a ten, using place value understanding and the properties of operations. Students also make sense of equations that represent addition methods Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding a one-digit number and two-digit number. | Interpret (orally and using other representations) methods for adding a one-digit and two-digit number that involve decomposing an addend to make a 10.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u5_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U5-L7",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 5 Lesson 7: Does It Make a New Ten?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add one-digit numbers and two-digit numbers, and recognize when a new ten will be composed. They write equations to represent their addition methods. Goals: Create sums that require composing a ten when adding by place and sums that do require composing a ten. | Explain (orally and with words or other representations) how to determine if a ten will be composed when adding within 100. | Find the value of sums within 100 and represent").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u5_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U5-L8",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 5 Lesson 8: Center Day 2. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice adding within 100. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding within 100.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u5_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U5-L9",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 5 Lesson 9: Add 2 Two-Digit Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add 2 two-digit numbers within 100 in any way that makes sense to them, including composing a ten. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding 2 two-digit numbers within 100, that include composing a ten.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u5_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U5-L10",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 5 Lesson 10: Tens and Tens, Ones and Ones. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add 2 two-digit numbers using methods based on place value. Goals: Interpret (orally) diagrams that represent a strategy for adding 2 two-digit numbers within 100 by place.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u5_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U5-L11",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 5 Lesson 11: How Did You Do That?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add 2 two-digit numbers, with composing a ten, using methods based on place value and properties of operation and make sense of equations that represent addition methods. Goals: Interpret (orally) base-ten diagrams and equations that represent strategies for adding 2 two-digit numbers by place. | Present (using words and other representations) strategies for adding 2 two-digit numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u5_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U5-L12",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 5 Lesson 12: Add It Up. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add 2 two-digit numbers, with composing a ten, using methods based on place value and properties of operations. Students write equations to represent addition methods. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding 2 two-digit numbers and represent a strategy using equations.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u5_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U5-L13",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 5 Lesson 13: Center Day 3. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice adding 2 two-digit numbers with composing a ten. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding 2 two-digit numbers that may require composing a ten.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u5_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U5-L14",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 5 Lesson 14: Food Drive. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply their understanding of adding two-digit numbers to a real-world context. Goals: Present (using words and other representations) solutions for a real-world problem involving adding within 100 that meets given constraints.").
%   Unit 6
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u6_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U6-L1",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 6 Lesson 1: Compare Lengths. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare the lengths of objects by lining up the endpoints and to order objects by length. Goals: Explain (orally) a strategy for comparing the length of two objects and ordering up to three objects by length. | Use “longer than” and “shorter than” to compare (orally and in writing) the length of up to three objects.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u6_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U6-L2",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 6 Lesson 2: Compare the Lengths of Objects Indirectly. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare the lengths of two objects indirectly by comparing each with the length of a third object. Goals: Use “longer than” and “shorter than” (orally and in writing) to compare objects that are shorter and longer than the length of a given object.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u6_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U6-L3",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 6 Lesson 3: Choose Objects to Compare Length Indirectly. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare the lengths of two objects that cannot be compared directly. Goals: Explain (orally) how to select and use a tool to compare two lengths indirectly.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u6_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U6-L4",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 6 Lesson 4: Center Day 1. The purpose of this lesson is to practice adding and subtracting within 100. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding and comparing numbers within 100.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u6_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U6-L5",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 6 Lesson 5: Measure with Connecting Cubes. The purpose of this lesson is to understand that a connecting cube tower with X cubes in it can be described as being “X cubes long” and to use connecting cube towers to measure objects in connecting cube lengths. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the meaning of the term “length.” | Use connecting cubes to measure the length of objects and express the length as “__ cubes long.”").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u6_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U6-L6",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 6 Lesson 6: Measure with Paper Clips. The purpose of this lesson is to measure length by iterating same-size length units with no gaps or overlaps. Goals: Explain (orally) how to use multiple copies of a shorter object to measure the length of an object without gaps or overlaps.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u6_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U6-L7",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 6 Lesson 7: Measure Length with Different Length Units. The purpose of this lesson is for students to measure lengths of objects using different length units and to understand that the number associated with a length depends on the chosen unit. Goals: Use different length units to measure the same length and describe (orally) observations about the measurements.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u6_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U6-L8",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 6 Lesson 8: Groups up to 110. The purpose of this lesson is to measure length and count and read numbers to 110. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for organizing and counting length units when measuring a length up to 110 length units. | Match (orally) base-ten diagrams and base-ten numerals that represent the same value.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u6_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U6-L9",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 6 Lesson 9: Write Numbers to 120. The purpose of this lesson is to count, read, and write numbers up to 120 in a measurement context. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for organizing and counting length units when measuring a length up to 120 length units. | Represent a base-ten diagram with a base-ten numeral up to 120.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u6_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U6-L10",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 6 Lesson 10: Center Day 2. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice measuring and adding within 100. Goals: Choose and use length units to estimate and measure the length of objects.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u6_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U6-L11",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 6 Lesson 11: How Long Are Our Shoes?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use addition and subtraction to solve story problems about measurement. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the phrases “how much longer” and “how much shorter” refer to finding an unknown difference. | Explain (orally) strategies for solving Add To and Compare problems involving measurement.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u6_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U6-L12",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 6 Lesson 12: Compare Measurements. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve Compare story problems about measurements. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for representing and solving Compare, Smaller Unknown and Compare, Bigger Unknown problems involving length.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u6_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U6-L13",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 6 Lesson 13: Solve Take From Story Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve Take From problems, with unknowns in all positions, in a way that makes sense to them. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for representing and solving a Take From, Start Unknown problem. | Interpret (orally) a diagram that represents Take From problems with unknowns in all positions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u6_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U6-L14",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 6 Lesson 14: Which Equation Matches?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to analyze story problems and match addition and subtraction equations to them. Goals: Match (orally) story problems and equations with a symbol for the unknown. | Match (orally) story problems that can be represented with addition, subtraction, or both operations.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u6_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U6-L15",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 6 Lesson 15: Write Equations for Story Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve story problems with unknowns in all positions using addition and subtraction. Students write equations to represent each story problem. Goals: Present (using words or other representations) a strategy for solving addition and subtraction story problems with unknowns in all positions. | Represent a strategy for solving an addition or subtraction problem with an equation.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u6_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U6-L16",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 6 Lesson 16: Center Day 3. The purpose of this lesson is to practice working with numbers to 120 and measuring lengths. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for estimating and counting a collection of up to 120 objects.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u6_l17, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U6-L17",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 6 Lesson 17: Class Quilt. The purpose of this lesson is for students to measure length and cut paper to a specified length. Goals: Use tools to create a design that follows constraints about length.").
%   Unit 7
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u7_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U7-L1",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 7 Lesson 1: Shapes That Are Solid. The purpose of this lesson is for students to sort three-dimensional shapes and to use their own language to describe the shapes. Goals: Describe (orally) three-dimensional shapes, using informal language. | Explain (orally) approaches for sorting three- dimensional shapes in different ways.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u7_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U7-L2",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 7 Lesson 2: Build Shapes from Other Shapes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use three-dimensional shapes to compose larger shapes. Goals: Create a given three-dimensional shape from smaller three-dimensional shapes. | Describe (orally) three-dimensional shapes and objects composed of three-dimensional shapes.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u7_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U7-L3",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 7 Lesson 3: Shapes That Are Flat. The purpose of this lesson is for students to describe two-dimensional shapes, using their own language, and to sort the shapes and explain how they sorted them. Goals: Describe (orally) two-dimensional shapes, using informal language. | Match (orally) two-dimensional shapes that have the same attributes.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u7_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U7-L4",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 7 Lesson 4: Draw Flat Shapes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to draw and describe two-dimensional shapes. As students draw the shapes and describe them, they develop increasingly precise mathematical language. Goals: Draw and describe (orally) two-dimensional shapes, including using shape names (“triangle,” “rectangle”) and geometric attributes (“sides,” “corners”).").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u7_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U7-L5",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 7 Lesson 5: Some Triangles, All Triangles. The purpose of this lesson is for students to identify defining and nondefining attributes of triangles. Students draw triangles, based on defining attributes. Goals: Draw (orally) examples and nonexamples of triangles. | Generalize (orally) that the term “triangle” refers to a flat shape with three straight sides and three corners.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u7_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U7-L6",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 7 Lesson 6: Rectangles and Squares. The purpose of this lesson is for students to identify defining and nondefining attributes of rectangles and squares. Students draw rectangles and squares as well as non-examples of rectangles and squares. Goals: Draw (orally) examples and nonexamples of rectangles and squares. | Generalize (orally and in writing) that the term “rectangle” refers to a flat shape with four straight sides and four square corners and that the term “square” refers to a rectangle with all sides that are the sa").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u7_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U7-L7",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 7 Lesson 7: Put Together Flat Shapes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compose larger shapes from pattern blocks and describe the shapes. Goals: Create two-dimensional shapes and figures composed of smaller two-dimensional shapes. | Describe (orally and using words or other representations) two-dimensional shapes and figures composed of two-dimensional shapes.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u7_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U7-L8",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 7 Lesson 8: Center Day 1. The purpose of this lesson is for students to work with two-dimensional and three-dimensional shapes as well as to practice addition and subtraction. Goals: Create and describe (orally) a three-dimensional object composed of smaller three-dimensional shapes.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u7_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U7-L9",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 7 Lesson 9: Equal Pieces. The purpose of this lesson is for students to partition circles and rectangles into halves and fourths and to determine whether a shape is partitioned into equal pieces. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the terms “halves” and “fourths.” | Explain (orally) how to partition a shape into equal- size pieces, including halves and fourths.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u7_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U7-L10",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 7 Lesson 10: One of the Pieces, All of the Pieces. The purpose of this lesson is for students to partition circles and rectangles into halves and fourths, and to use precise language to describe each piece as half or a fourth of the whole shape. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the phrases “a half of,” “a fourth of,” and “a quarter of.” | Describe (orally) a whole shape as two halves or as four fourths. | Describe (orally) partitioned shapes and their pieces, using “halves,” “fourths,” “quarters").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u7_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U7-L11",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 7 Lesson 11: A Bigger Piece. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare the sizes of halves and fourths of the same shape and to understand that partitioning a shape into more equal pieces creates smaller pieces. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) halves and fourths of the same shape. | Critique (orally and using words or other representations) arguments that compare the size of halves and fourths of the same shape.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u7_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U7-L12",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 7 Lesson 12: Center Day 2. The purpose of this lesson is for students to work with shapes and numbers. Goals: Describe (orally) a two-dimensional shape and draw a shape, based on the given description.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u7_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U7-L13",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 7 Lesson 13: It’s Time to Learn about Clocks. The purpose of this lesson is for students to tell and write the time in hours. Goals: Comprehend (in written and spoken language) the meaning of the terms “hour” and “o’clock.”refers to a way to name the time of day to the hour. | Explain (orally) how to read and represent the time to the hour on an analog and digital clock. | Match (orally) analog and digital clo").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u7_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U7-L14",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 7 Lesson 14: Half of the Clock. The purpose of this lesson is for students to learn about the position of the hands on an analog clock at half past the hour. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the phrase “half past.” | Interpret (orally) an analog clock and determine the time to the hour and half hour.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u7_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U7-L15",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 7 Lesson 15: Write Times. The purpose of this lesson is for students to understand that times called “half past” are represented as ___:30. Students write the time in hours and half hours to match analog clocks. Goals: Represent the time shown on an analog clock to the hour and the half hour, using digits.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u7_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U7-L16",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 7 Lesson 16: Hard Times. The purpose of this lesson is for students to show and write the time in hours and half hours. Goals: Critique (orally and using words or other representations) arguments about how to read the time on an analog clock. | Interpret and represent times to the hour and the half hour, using digital and analog clocks.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u7_l17, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U7-L17",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 7 Lesson 17: Center Day 3. The purpose of this lesson is for students to work with shapes and addition and subtraction. Goals: Determine the information needed to identify a shape. Ask (orally) questions to elicit that information.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u7_l18, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U7-L18",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 7 Lesson 18: Halves and Fourths in Our World. The purpose of this lesson is for students to recognize objects in their environment that are partitioned into halves and fourths. Goals: Create and describe (orally) drawings of real-world situations that include rectangles and circles partitioned into halves and fourths.").
%   Unit 8
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u8_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U8-L1",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 8 Lesson 1: Addition Fluency within 10. The purpose of this lesson is for students to develop fluency with sums within 10. Goals: Identify (orally) sums within 10 that are known and not yet known and explain (orally) strategies for determining the value of sums that are not yet known.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u8_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U8-L2",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 8 Lesson 2: Relate Addition and Subtraction. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use the relationship between addition and subtraction to fluently add and subtract within 10. Goals: Explain (orally) how to determine the values that make equations within 10 true, including using the relationship between addition and subtraction. | Identify differences within 10 that are known and not yet known and explain (orally) how to use a related sum to determine the val").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u8_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U8-L3",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 8 Lesson 3: Add and Subtract within 20. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add and subtract within 20. Goals: Present (using words and other representations) and compare and contrast strategies for adding and subtracting within 20.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u8_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U8-L4",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 8 Lesson 4: Change Unknown Story Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve Add To and Take From, Change Unknown story problems. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving Add To and Take From, Change Unknown problems within 20, including using the relationship between addition and subtraction.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u8_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U8-L5",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 8 Lesson 5: Put Together and Take Apart Story Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve Put Together/Take Apart, Addend Unknown story problems. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving Put Together/ Take Apart, Addend Unknown story problems. | Match (orally) Put Together/Take Apart problems and equations with a symbol for the unknown.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u8_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U8-L6",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 8 Lesson 6: Compare Story Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve Compare, Difference Unknown story problems. Goals: Ask (orally and in writing) questions that can be answered using given information, including a diagram. | Explain (orally) strategies for solving Compare, Difference Unknown story problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u8_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U8-L7",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 8 Lesson 7: Count Large Collections. The purpose of this lesson is for students to organize, count, and represent a collection of up to 120 objects or images using place value understanding. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for counting images within 120. | Represent a strategy for organizing and counting a collection of objects within 120.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u8_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U8-L8",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 8 Lesson 8: Show Me All the Ways. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent two-digit numbers in different ways to demonstrate place value understanding. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) different base-ten representations of the same two-digit number. | Represent the same two-digit number in different ways.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u8_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U8-L9",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 8 Lesson 9: Solve Number Riddles. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use their understanding of place value to solve number riddles. Goals: Use clues based on place value to determine (orally) unknown two-digit numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade1_u8_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G1-U8-L10",
    "IM Grade1 Unit 8 Lesson 10: Write Number Riddles. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply place value reasoning to write and solve number riddles. Goals: Use place value understanding to create (in writing) and solve number riddles.").
% ─ grade2 ─
%   Unit 1
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u1_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U1-L1",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 1 Lesson 1: Add and Subtract within 10. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add and subtract within 10. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding and subtracting within 10.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u1_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U1-L2",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 1 Lesson 2: Relate Addition and Subtraction within 10. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find the number that makes equations true and write addition and related subtraction equations within 10. Goals: Find the value of an unknown addend for a sum of 10. | Represent situations with an unknown addend and sums of 10 with addition and subtraction equations.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u1_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U1-L3",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 1 Lesson 3: Relate Addition and Subtraction within 20. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find the number that makes equations true within 20. Goals: Explain (orally) a strategy for finding the number that makes an equation with a sum of 20 true.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u1_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U1-L4",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 1 Lesson 4: Add and Subtract Your Way. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add and subtract within 20 in a way that makes sense to them. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding and subtracting within 20.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u1_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U1-L5",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 1 Lesson 5: Add within 50. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add within 50. Students find the value of sums within 50 in any way that makes sense to them. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding within 50.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u1_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U1-L6",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 1 Lesson 6: Center Day 1. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice adding and subtracting within 10, 20, or 50. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding within 50.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u1_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U1-L7",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 1 Lesson 7: Collect and Represent Data. The mathematical purpose of this lesson is to elicit and build on students’ previous understandings and experiences with organizing and representing data. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally and in writing) representations of the same data. | Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the term “data.” | Create (using words and other representations) a representation of data.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u1_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U1-L8",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 1 Lesson 8: Interpret Picture Graphs. The purpose of this lesson is for students to read and interpret a picture graph, which is a standard way of representing data. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the term “picture graph.” | Determine (orally and in writing) if a question can be answered by a given picture graph and answer questions about data. | Interpret (orally) data represented in a picture graph.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u1_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U1-L9",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 1 Lesson 9: Interpret Bar Graphs. The purpose of this lesson is for students to interpret data in a bar graph in order to answer questions. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the term “bar graph.” | Interpret (orally and in writing) data represented in a bar graph. | Use the features of a bar graph to answer questions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u1_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U1-L10",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 1 Lesson 10: Represent Data Using Picture Graphs and Bar Graphs. The purpose of this lesson is for students to attend to the features of picture graphs and bar graphs as they represent a given set of categorical data in picture graphs and bar graphs. Goals: Represent given data using a picture graph and a bar graph.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u1_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U1-L11",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 1 Lesson 11: Questions about Data. The purpose of this lesson is for students to ask and answer questions about a given set of categorical data represented in picture graphs and bar graphs. Goals: Ask (in writing) questions that can be answered about data represented in picture graphs and bar graphs. | Explain (orally and in writing) how to use the features of picture graphs and bar graphs to answer questions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u1_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U1-L12",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 1 Lesson 12: Center Day 2. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice organizing data and using graphs to represent it. Students also practice adding and subtracting within 10, 20, or 50. Goals: Ask (orally) and answer questions that can be answered about the data represented in a picture graph or bar graph. | Represent data using picture graphs and bar graphs.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u1_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U1-L13",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 1 Lesson 13: Use Bar Graphs to Compare. The purpose of this lesson is for students to make sense of and solve Compare problems using the structure of a bar graph and equations. Goals: Use a bar graph to solve Compare, Unknown Difference problems within 20 and represent comparisons with an equation. | Use “more” and “fewer” to compare (orally and in writing) data represented in a bar graph.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u1_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U1-L14",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 1 Lesson 14: Use Diagrams to Compare. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use their understanding of bar graphs to interpret tape diagrams and solve Compare problems with the difference unknown within 20. Goals: Comprehend (in written and spoken language) the term “diagram” refers to a drawing or picture that represents quantities. | Interpret (orally) a tape diagram that represents a comparison.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u1_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U1-L15",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 1 Lesson 15: Diagrams with All Kinds of Compare Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to connect Compare problems with unknowns in all positions to tape diagrams. Goals: Match (orally and in writing) tape diagrams, equations, and Compare story problems that represent the same relationships within 100.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u1_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U1-L16",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 1 Lesson 16: Solve All Kinds of Compare Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve Compare problems with an unknown in all positions. Goals: Solve Compare problems with unknowns in all all positions. | Use a tape diagram to interpret and solve Compare story problems with unknowns in all positions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u1_l17, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U1-L17",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 1 Lesson 17: Center Day 3. The purpose of this lesson is for students to count large groups of objects by creating smaller groups of 5 or 10. Students practice adding within 50 or representing data with graphs. Goals: Explain (orally) a strategy for counting and representing a collection of up to 120 objects.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u1_l18, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U1-L18",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 1 Lesson 18: Class Surveys. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use what they have learned about data, bar graphs, and tape diagrams to create a survey and to organize, collect, and represent data. Goals: Represent data collected from a peer-survey with graphs, diagrams, and equations.").
%   Unit 2
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u2_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U2-L1",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 2 Lesson 1: Add and Subtract to Compare. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add and subtract within 100 without composing or decomposing a ten. Students find sums and differences in a way that makes sense to them and compare methods based on place value and the relation Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) strategies for finding an unknown difference that involve addition and subtraction. | Explain (orally) strategies for solving problems within 100 that do not involve composing or decomposing a ten.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u2_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U2-L2",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 2 Lesson 2: Find the Unknown Addend. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find the value of unknown addends by adding or subtracting within 100. Goals: Explain (orally) representations and strategies used to find an unknown addend, including those based on place value.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u2_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U2-L3",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 2 Lesson 3: Add or Subtract to Solve Story Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve story problems involving addition and subtraction within 100 without composing or decomposing a ten. Goals: Solve story problems and compare and contrast (orally) strategies, including those based on place value.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u2_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U2-L4",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 2 Lesson 4: Center Day 1. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice addition and subtraction within 100 that does not require composing or decomposing a ten. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding within 100.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u2_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U2-L5",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 2 Lesson 5: Subtract Your Way. The purpose of this lesson is for students to subtract a one-digit number from a two-digit number and describe decomposing a ten when subtracting by place. Goals: Explain (orally) an approach for subtracting a one- digit number from a two-digit number. | Interpret (orally and using other representations) subtraction strategies that involve decomposing a ten.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u2_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U2-L6",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 2 Lesson 6: Compare Methods for Subtraction. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare methods for subtracting a one-digit number from a two-digit number with and without decomposing a ten. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) strategies and recording methods for subtracting a one-digit number from a two-digit number. | Describe (orally) how a base-ten diagram and equations represent the same subtraction strategy.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u2_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U2-L7",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 2 Lesson 7: Subtract 2 Digits. The purpose of this lesson is for students to subtract a two-digit number from a two-digit number when a ten is decomposed to subtract by place. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for subtracting a two-digit number from a two-digit number, including those that use base-ten representations.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u2_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U2-L8",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 2 Lesson 8: Different Ways to Decompose. The purpose of this lesson is for students to make sense of different methods for subtracting a two-digit number from a two-digit number and describe how the methods are the same and different. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally and in writing) methods that represent decomposing a ten to subtract 2 two-digit numbers. | Explain (orally) a strategy for subtracting 2 two-digit numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u2_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U2-L9",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 2 Lesson 9: Add and Subtract within 100. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add and subtract within 100, including composing and decomposing a ten, using strategies based on place value and the properties of operations. Goals: Match (orally) addition and subtraction expressions and base-ten diagrams that represent the same value. | Present (using words and other representations) strategies for adding and subtracting within 100.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u2_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U2-L10",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 2 Lesson 10: Center Day 2. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice adding and subtracting within 100 using methods based on place value understanding, the properties of operations, and the relationship between addition and subtraction. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for subtracting within 100.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u2_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U2-L11",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 2 Lesson 11: How Do You Solve Story Problems?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent and solve story problems involving addition and subtraction within 50 that require composing or decomposing a ten when adding or subtracting by place. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) representations used to make sense of and solve Compare story problems. | Represent and solve Compare story problems within 50 that require composing or decomposing a ten.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u2_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U2-L12",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 2 Lesson 12: Story Problems and Diagrams. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve story problems of different problem types within 100. Students interpret tape diagrams and connect them to different types of story problems. Goals: Match (orally and in writing) Compare or Put Together/Take Apart problems and tape diagrams that represent the same relationships. | Represent and solve story problems within 100.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u2_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U2-L13",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 2 Lesson 13: Story Problems and Equations. The purpose of this lesson is for students to make sense of equations and connect them to the quantities in different types of story problems. Students solve story problems of different problem types within 100 that require composing or dec Goals: Match (orally) story problems and equations that represent the same quantities and relationships. | Represent and solve Add To and Put Together story problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u2_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U2-L14",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 2 Lesson 14: Solve It Your Way. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent and solve one- and two-step story problems. Students use representations to make sense of problems, support their calculations, and explain their thinking. Goals: Represent and solve one- and two-step Add To, Result Unknown problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u2_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U2-L15",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 2 Lesson 15: Does My Estimation Make Sense?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use estimation strategies based on place value and to decide if estimates for answers to one- and two-step story problems make sense. Goals: Comprehend (in written and spoken language) that an “estimate” for a story problem refers to an answer that makes sense for the actions and quantities in the story, but is not found by calculating the exact value. | Determine (orally and in writing) whether an estimate for the an").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u2_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U2-L16",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 2 Lesson 16: Center Day 3. The purpose of this lesson is for students to interpret diagrams, solve story problems, and add and subtract within 100. Goals: Create (orally) and solve a story problem that represents a tape diagram.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u2_l17, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U2-L17",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 2 Lesson 17: Our Store’s Inventory. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply strategies for adding and subtracting within 100 in the context of a store. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving problems that involve addition and subtraction.").
%   Unit 3
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u3_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U3-L1",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 3 Lesson 1: Standard Units of Measure. The purpose of this lesson is for students to measure by iterating same-size length units and identify the need for standard units of measurement. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the term “length unit” refers to the length of the object you use to measure. | Use same-size length units to measure the length of objects and express (orally) the length as the number of objects without gaps or overlaps.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u3_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U3-L2",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 3 Lesson 2: Measure in Centimeters. The purpose of this lesson is for students to measure in centimeters. Goals: Choose tools and explain (orally) how to use them to measure the length of objects in centimeters. | Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the term “centimeter.”").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u3_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U3-L3",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 3 Lesson 3: Create and Use a Ruler. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use a ruler to measure and compare lengths in centimeters. Goals: Create a centimeter ruler and describe (orally) how it represents lengths in centimeters. | Explain (orally) how to determine how much longer one object is than another.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u3_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U3-L4",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 3 Lesson 4: Measure and Estimate in Centimeters. The purpose of this lesson is for students to estimate and measure lengths in centimeters. Students use a ruler for the first time. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) that an “estimate” of the length of an object is a guess you make based on what you know about the object and the size of the length unit. | Explain (orally) how to estimate the length of an object. | Use a ruler to measure the length o").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u3_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U3-L5",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 3 Lesson 5: Measure in Meters. The purpose of this lesson is for students to learn that the meter is a larger unit of metric length measurement. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) measurements made with different tools or expressed in different units. | Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the term “meter.” | Use rulers and meter sticks to measure length in centimeters and meters.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u3_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U3-L6",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 3 Lesson 6: Compare Reptile Lengths in Story Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve Compare story problems within 100 involving length. Goals: Create and solve Compare, Larger Unknown and Compare, Smaller Unknown story problems about length. | Match (orally) tape diagrams and Compare story problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u3_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U3-L7",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 3 Lesson 7: Center Day 1. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add and subtract within 100 as well as tell and solve math stories. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for finding the unknown number that makes an equation true.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u3_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U3-L8",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 3 Lesson 8: What Is an Inch?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to learn that an inch is a standard length unit in the U.S. customary system and use it to measure length. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the term “inch.” | Use a ruler to measure length in inches.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u3_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U3-L9",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 3 Lesson 9: From Feet to Inches. The purpose of this lesson is for students to learn about a larger unit of customary measurement—the foot. Students measure in inches and feet, compare their measurements, and generalize about the relationship between the size of a length u Goals: Choose the length units and tools to measure the length of objects and explain (orally) the choices. | Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the term “foot” and “feet” in the context of length measurement. | Generalize (orally) that it takes more smaller unit").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u3_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U3-L10",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 3 Lesson 10: Measure with a Torn Tape. The purpose of this lesson is for students to measure objects without using 0 as the starting point. Goals: Create equations that represent the length of an object when the starting point of the measuring tool does not line up with 0. | Explain (orally) how to measure an object when starting from a non-zero tick mark on a ruler.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u3_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U3-L11",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 3 Lesson 11: Saree Silk Stories: Necklaces and Bracelets. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve Take From story problems within 100 in the context of length. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving Take From problems about length. | Interpret (orally) tape diagrams that represent Take From problems about length.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u3_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U3-L12",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 3 Lesson 12: Saree Silk Stories: Friendship Bracelets. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent and solve two-step story problems. Students use representations to make sense of problems, support their calculations, and explain their thinking. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for representing and solving two-step Take From and Compare problems about length.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u3_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U3-L13",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 3 Lesson 13: Center Day 2. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice estimating and measuring length. Goals: Explain (orally) how to estimate and measure the length of objects.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u3_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U3-L14",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 3 Lesson 14: What Is a Line Plot?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to learn about the ways a line plot can be used to represent data collected from measuring objects. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the term “line plot.” | Interpret (orally and in writing) the features of a line plot and use line plots to answer questions about measurement data.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u3_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U3-L15",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 3 Lesson 15: Create Line Plots. The purpose of this lesson is for students to create line plots to represent numerical data. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) line plots that represent the same data. | Create a line plot to represent measurement data.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u3_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U3-L16",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 3 Lesson 16: Interpret Measurement Data. The purpose of this lesson is for students to create and interpret a line plot. Goals: Create a line plot with an appropriate scale to represent measurement data. | Interpret (orally and in writing) line plots with a scale that does not start at 0.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u3_l17, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U3-L17",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 3 Lesson 17: Center Day 3. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice adding, subtracting, and measuring length to create line plots. Goals: Create a line plot to represent measurement data and ask (orally) questions that can be answered about the data in a line plot.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u3_l18, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U3-L18",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 3 Lesson 18: Make a Yardstick. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply their understanding of addition, subtraction, and measurement to build their own yardstick. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally and in writing) student- created yardsticks and use an understanding of same-size length units to describe differences in measurement results. | Explain (orally) the strategies used to mark each inch mark to create a yardstick.").
%   Unit 4
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u4_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U4-L1",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 4 Lesson 1: Whole Numbers on the Number Line. The purpose of this lesson is for students to understand the structure of the number line and learn how whole numbers can be represented on the number line with tick marks and points. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the term “number line” refers to a diagram that represents numbers. | Create a number line and describe (orally) its features. | Represent whole numbers by drawing points and labeling tick marks on a number line.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u4_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U4-L2",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 4 Lesson 2: Features of a Number Line. The purpose of this lesson is for students to identify and describe the defining features of the number line. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the term “number line” refers to a diagram that represents numbers as lengths from 0 using equally- spaced tick marks or points. | Describe (orally) the structure of a number line and explain how to revise a number line.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u4_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U4-L3",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 4 Lesson 3: Unlabeled Tick Marks. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent numbers within 100 on number lines that do not label each tick mark. Goals: Explain (orally) how to locate a whole number on a number line that does not label each number. | Interpret (orally) number lines with unlabeled tick marks, including those that do not start at 0.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u4_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U4-L4",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 4 Lesson 4: Compare Numbers on a Number Line. The purpose of this lesson is for students to recognize that on a number line the numbers increase to the right and decrease to the left. Goals: Generalize (orally) that on the number line numbers “to the right” represent values that are greater than numbers “to the left” and that numbers “to the left” represent values that are less than numbers “to the right.” | Use a number line to compare 2 whole numbers and express th").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u4_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U4-L5",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 4 Lesson 5: Estimate on a Number Line. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use their understanding of length and the structure of a number line to estimate the location of a number on a number line. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for estimating the location of whole numbers on a number line.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u4_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U4-L6",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 4 Lesson 6: Center Day 1. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent numbers on a number line and to practice addition and subtraction within 100. Goals: Identify (orally) and represent whole numbers on a number line.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u4_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U4-L7",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 4 Lesson 7: Addition and Subtraction on the Number Line. The purpose of this lesson is for students to attend to the direction of the arrow on the number line to match addition and subtraction expressions. Goals: Match (orally and in writing) addition and subtraction expressions and number line diagrams.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u4_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U4-L8",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 4 Lesson 8: Equations on a Number Line. The purpose of this lesson is for students to write equations based on number lines and to represent equations on a number line. Goals: Create equations to represent number line diagrams that show addition or subtraction. | Represent addition and subtraction on a number line diagram.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u4_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U4-L9",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 4 Lesson 9: The Difference between Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent and compare different subtraction methods on the number line. Goals: Interpret (orally) number line diagrams that represent counting strategies for finding an unknown difference. | Represent strategies for finding an unknown difference using a number line diagram.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u4_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U4-L10",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 4 Lesson 10: Place Value and the Number Line. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare representations of addition and subtraction methods represented on the number line. Goals: Interpret (orally) base-ten diagrams and number line diagrams that represent place value strategies for addition and subtraction. | Use a number line to represent addition and subtraction strategies based on place value that do not require composing or decomposing a ten.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u4_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U4-L11",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 4 Lesson 11: Different Ways to Add and Subtract. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent sums and differences on a number line with an emphasis on the strategy of using a ten to count up or count back. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) number line diagrams that represent subtraction strategies based on place value reasoning. | Explain (using words or other representations) addition and subtraction strategies that may involve composing or decomposing a ten.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u4_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U4-L12",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 4 Lesson 12: Equations with Unknowns. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent addition and subtraction and to find unknown values using a number line and equations with a symbol for the unknown. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the phrase “jumped __ to the right” refers to addition on the number line and the phrase “jumped __ to the left” refers to subtraction. | Represent addition and subtraction situations using number lines and equations with a symbol for t").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u4_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U4-L13",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 4 Lesson 13: Represent Story Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to make connections between different representations of situations for sums and differences. Goals: Match (orally) tape diagrams, number lines, and equations that represent the same story problem. | Represent and solve Add To story problems with unknowns in all positions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u4_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U4-L14",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 4 Lesson 14: Center Day 2. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice adding and subtracting within 100 and representing addition and subtraction on the number line. Goals: Represent addition and subtraction within 100 on the number line.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u4_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U4-L15",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 4 Lesson 15: Tall Enough to Ride. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use two-digit numbers that are represented on a number line to solve problems. Goals: Interpret a number line that represents a real-world context and explain (orally) how to use the number line diagram to make decisions.").
%   Unit 5
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u5_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U5-L1",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 5 Lesson 1: How Do We Compose a Hundred?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to make sense of a hundred as a unit composed of 10 tens or 100 ones. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) that “a hundred” is a unit made up of 10 tens or 100 ones. | Explain (orally) strategies for representing 100 with the greatest and fewest number of tens and ones.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u5_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U5-L2",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 5 Lesson 2: Make Hundreds. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent hundreds in different ways. Goals: Describe (orally) the relationship between the number of tens and the number of hundreds that represent the same value. | Represent multiples of 10 and 100 using base-ten blocks and base-ten diagrams.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u5_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U5-L3",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 5 Lesson 3: Compose 3-Digit Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use base-ten representations to build an understanding of the digits in three-digit numbers. Goals: Present (using words and other representations) representations of a value within 1,000. | Represent a three-digit number using the fewest number of each unit.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u5_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U5-L4",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 5 Lesson 4: Write 3-Digit Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use their understanding of place value to identify and write three-digit numbers. Goals: Create a three-digit number given the number of hundreds, tens, and ones. | Describe (orally) relationships between the amount of each unit and the value written as a three-digit number.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u5_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U5-L5",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 5 Lesson 5: Expanded Form of Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use expanded form and base-ten numerals to represent numbers within 1,000. Goals: Comprehend (in written and spoken language) the meaning of “expanded form.” | Use three-digit numbers and expanded form to represent the same base-ten diagram and describe (orally) how they represent the same value.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u5_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U5-L6",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 5 Lesson 6: Represent Numbers in Different Ways. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent numbers using unit form, base-ten numerals, expanded form, and words. Goals: Determine (orally and in writing) the written names of numbers represented in different ways. | Represent the same three-digit number in multiple ways, including number names, expanded form, base-ten numerals, and a base-ten diagram.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u5_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U5-L7",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 5 Lesson 7: Center Day 1. The purpose of this lesson is for students to work with place value and practice addition and subtraction within 100. Goals: Describe (orally) and identify three-digit numbers using clues based on place value.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u5_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U5-L8",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 5 Lesson 8: Three-Digit Numbers on the Number Line. The purpose of this lesson is for students to locate and label three-digit numbers on number lines. Goals: Represent whole numbers up to 1,000 as lengths from 0 on a number line.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u5_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U5-L9",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 5 Lesson 9: Compare Numbers on the Number Line. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare three-digit numbers using a number line. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) representations used to compare 2 three-digit numbers, including base-ten diagrams and number line diagrams. | Explain (orally) strategies for comparing three-digit numbers and express comparisons using <, >, and =.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u5_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U5-L10",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 5 Lesson 10: Place Value Comparisons (Part 1). The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare three-digit numbers using their understanding of place value. Goals: Explain (orally) how to use base-ten diagrams to compare three-digit numbers. | Generalize (orally) that when comparing three-digit numbers it is helpful to start by comparing the value of the hundreds, followed by the tens, and then ones.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u5_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U5-L11",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 5 Lesson 11: Place Value Comparisons (Part 2). The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare three-digit numbers using their understanding of place value. Goals: Explain (orally) methods for comparing three-digit numbers based on place value.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u5_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U5-L12",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 5 Lesson 12: Order Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to order numbers from least to greatest and greatest to least. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for ordering three-digit numbers based on place value understanding and the relative position of numbers on a number line.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u5_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U5-L13",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 5 Lesson 13: Center Day 2. The purpose of this lesson is for students to order, compare, and describe three-digit numbers using their understanding of place value. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for ordering three-digit numbers based on place value.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u5_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U5-L14",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 5 Lesson 14: Around the School. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use what they know about place value to estimate what given numbers could represent in a school. Goals: Create (orally and in writing) examples and non- examples of collections of objects that could be represented by a given number. | Explain (orally) estimation strategies.").
%   Unit 6
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L1",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 1: Identify and Sort Shapes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to recognize and name shapes, based on the numbers of sides and vertices (corners). Students name triangles, quadrilaterals, pentagons, and hexagons. Goals: Comprehend (in written and spoken language) that the terms “quadrilateral,” “pentagon,” and “hexagon” refer to categories of shapes that are each defined by a number of straight sides and corners. | Describe (orally) the attributes of triangles, quadrilaterals, pentagons, and hex").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L2",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 2: Draw Shapes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to recognize and draw shapes that have a specific number of sides or corners. Goals: Draw and identify (orally and in writing) shapes that have a given number of sides or corners.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L3",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 3: Specific Side Lengths. The purpose of this lesson is for students to recognize and draw shapes that have sides with a given length. Students also revisit and practice measuring lengths. Goals: Describe (orally) the attributes of shapes and name (orally and in writing) quadrilaterals, pentagons, and hexagons. | Identify (orally and in writing) shapes that have given side lengths and draw shapes with specific side lengths.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L4",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 4: Solid Shapes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to recognize and describe three-dimensional (solid) shapes, based on their geometric attributes (faces). Goals: Comprehend the meaning of the term “cube.” | Describe (orally) the relationship between a solid shape and a composition of flat shapes. | Present (using words and other representations) descriptions of the attributes of solid shapes.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L5",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 5: Center Day 1. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice describing, naming, and drawing triangles, quadrilaterals, and hexagons, based on their defining attributes. Goals: Explain (orally) how to draw a given shape by describing its attributes. | Identify (orally) a shape, based on given attributes. Ask questions to elicit the attributes needed to identify the shape.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L6",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 6: Compose and Decompose Shapes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compose shapes and to recognize shapes that are made up of equal-size shapes. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) compositions of shapes that form the same given shape. | Create a shape composed of equal-size smaller shapes and identify (orally and in writing) the shapes.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L7",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 7: Make Halves, Thirds, and Fourths. The purpose of this lesson is for students to recognize halves, thirds, and fourths, understanding that these terms describe equal pieces of the same whole. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of “a third,” “thirds,” “halves,” and “fourths.” | Draw to partition rectangles and circles into halves, thirds, and fourths, and explain (orally) strategies for ensuring all pieces are of equal size.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L8",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 8: Are All Pieces Created Equal?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to understand that equal pieces of an identical whole do not need to be the same shape. Goals: Draw and describe (orally) circles and rectangles that are partitioned into “halves,” “thirds,” and “fourths.” | Generalize (orally) that equal-size pieces of the same whole can look different but remain the same size and have the same name.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L9",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 9: You Took the Whole Thing!. The purpose of this lesson is for students to recognize two halves, three thirds, and four fourths as one whole. Goals: Describe (orally) an equal-size piece, using the phrases “half of,” “a third of,” and “a quarter of” a shape. | Describe (orally) two halves, three thirds, and four fourths as one “whole.”").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L10",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 10: Center Day 2. The purpose of this lesson is for students to work with shapes. Goals: Match (orally) shapes that have a shared attribute and draw a shape that has the same shared attribute.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L11",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 11: Tell Time with Halves and Quarters. The purpose of this lesson is for students to tell time with an analog clock, using the words “half past,” “quarter past,” and “quarter till.” Goals: Determine (orally) the time shown on an analog clock and express the time, using the phrases “half past,” “quarter past,” and “quarter till.” | Match partitioned circles and phrases (“half past,” “quarter past,” or “quarter till”) that represent the same time on an analog clock.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L12",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 12: Count by 5 to Tell Time. The purpose of this lesson is for students to tell time to the nearest 5 minutes on an analog clock. Goals: Determine (orally and in writing) the time on a clock to the nearest 5 minutes, and explain (orally) a strategy for telling time.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L13",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 13: Is It a.m. or p.m.?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to read and write the time with analog and digital clocks, using “a.m.” and “p.m.” Goals: Comprehend that the notation “a.m.” refers to times of day in the morning and “p.m.” refers to times of day in the afternoon and night. | Explain (orally) how to determine if a time should be labeled as “a.m.” or “p.m.”").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L14",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 14: Center Day 3. The purpose of this lesson is for students to recognize shapes, to describe the attributes of shapes, and to practice adding and subtracting within 100. Goals: Name (orally and in writing) shapes found in picture books, based on their attributes.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L15",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 15: Identify Pennies, Nickels, and Dimes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to identify pennies, nickels, and dimes, and to find the total value of a set of coins. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) that the terms “penny,” “nickel,” and “dime” refer to coins with values in cents. | Comprehend that the term “cents” refers to a unit of money and that the notation ¢ can be used to represent cents. | Identify (orally and in writing) th").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L16",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 16: Identify Quarters. The purpose of this lesson is for students to identify quarters and to find the total value of a set of coins that includes quarters. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) that the term “quarter” refers to a coin with a value of 25 cents. | Identify (orally and in writing) the names of coins and explain (orally) a strategy for finding the value of a collection of coins. | Represent (using words or other f").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l17, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L17",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 17: Let’s Make a Dollar. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add and subtract within 100 to find values of 100 cents, and to recognize a dollar as a unit of money with the same value as 100 cents. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) that the term “dollar” refers to a unit of money with the same value as 100 cents and that the notation $ can be used to represent dollars. | Find the value of a collection of coins that has a value greater than 100 cents. | Represent a").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l18, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L18",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 18: Money Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use addition and subtraction to solve story problems in the context of money. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving Add To and Take From story problems involving money.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l19, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L19",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 19: More Money Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve addition and subtraction story problems within 100, in the context of money. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving two-step Put Together/Take Apart and Compare problems. | Match (orally) diagrams and story problems, including two-step problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l20, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L20",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 20: Does My Answer Make Sense?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use estimation strategies, based on place value, to decide if answers to two- step story problems make sense. Goals: Critique (orally and in writing) estimates for solutions to two-step story problems. | Solve two-step story problems within 100 and explain (orally) strategies for determining if an answer is reasonable.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l21, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L21",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 21: Center Day 4. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare the value of coin collections and to work with shapes. Goals: Ask (orally) questions that encourage comparing two collections of coins, and compare the values of coin collections.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u6_l22, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U6-L22",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 6 Lesson 22: Spending Money. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve problems involving dollar amounts and to make decisions about spending money. Goals: Determine (orally) the consequences of spending an amount of money in a real-world problem. | Find the values of amounts of money in a real-world problem and present (using words and other representations) how much is spent, what it was spent on, and how much is left.").
%   Unit 7
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u7_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U7-L1",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 7 Lesson 1: Compare, Count On, and Count Back. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add or subtract within 1,000, using number relationships. Goals: Identify (orally and in writing) unknown numbers that complete a count by 10 or by 100. | Interpret (orally) number line diagrams that represent strategies for adding and subtracting within 100.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u7_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U7-L2",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 7 Lesson 2: Add and Subtract with Tens and Hundreds. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add and subtract multiples of 10 and 100 within 1,000. Goals: Represent adding and subtracting multiples of 10 or 100, with base-ten blocks, base-ten diagrams, and equations.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u7_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U7-L3",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 7 Lesson 3: Count On or Count Back to Subtract. The purpose of this lesson is for students to subtract within 1,000, using strategies that demonstrate an understanding of the relationship between addition and subtraction, including counting on and counting back. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for subtracting and strategies for finding the value of an unknown addend within 1,000. | Interpret (orally) representations of subtraction strategies that show taking away tens and ones and those that show counting by place value.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u7_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U7-L4",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 7 Lesson 4: Add and Subtract 3-Digit Numbers in Different Ways. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add and subtract within 1,000, without composing a ten or a hundred, using place-value understanding, properties of operations, and the relationship between addition and subtraction. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) approaches for adding and subtracting within 1,000 that do not include composing or decomposing units when adding by place. | Use different strategies and recording methods to find the values of sums and differences within 1,000.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u7_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U7-L5",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 7 Lesson 5: Center Day 1. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice adding numbers within 1,000. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding three-digit numbers that do not require composing units when adding by place.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u7_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U7-L6",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 7 Lesson 6: Use a Ten to Add within 1,000. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add a two-digit number to a three-digit number that requires composing a ten when adding by place. Goals: Explain (orally) how to determine whether a ten will be composed when adding a three-digit number and a two-digit number by place. | Find the values of sums within 1,000, and describe (orally) patterns in the digits when a ten is composed.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u7_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U7-L7",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 7 Lesson 7: Compose a Greater Unit. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add two-digit numbers and three-digit numbers and compose a ten or a hundred. Students relate composing a hundred to composing a ten. Goals: Explain (orally and using other representations) how to determine if a ten or a hundred will be composed when adding within 1,000. | Explain (orally) strategies for adding a three-digit number and a two-digit number.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u7_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U7-L8",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 7 Lesson 8: Compose Tens and Hundreds to Add. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add within 1,000, using place value-based strategies, by composing both a ten and a hundred. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) recording methods for adding within 1,000. | Explain (orally) strategies for adding two-digit and three-digit numbers, including composing two units.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u7_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U7-L9",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 7 Lesson 9: Add 3-Digit Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add 2 three-digit numbers. Goals: Critique (orally and in writing) methods for adding three-digit numbers. | Explain (orally) strategies for adding 2 three-digit numbers that include composing two units when adding by place.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u7_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U7-L10",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 7 Lesson 10: Add within 1,000. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add three-digit numbers, using strategies based on place value and the properties of operations. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for finding the value of an unknown addend within 1,000. | Explain (orally) strategies for finding the values of sums that are more and less challenging.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u7_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U7-L11",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 7 Lesson 11: Center Day 2. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice adding numbers within 1,000. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding three-digit numbers that may require composing units when adding by place.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u7_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U7-L12",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 7 Lesson 12: Decompose to Subtract. The purpose of this lesson is for students to decompose a ten in order to subtract within 1,000. Goals: Explain (orally) how to use base-ten blocks to represent subtraction within 1,000, including when a unit will be decomposed. | Explain (orally) strategies for subtracting within 1,000 when a ten would be decomposed when subtracting by place.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u7_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U7-L13",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 7 Lesson 13: Decompose Tens or Hundreds. The purpose of this lesson is for students to subtract from three-digit numbers, using place-value strategies that include decomposing a ten or a hundred. Goals: Interpret (orally) base-ten diagrams that represent subtraction strategies based on place value. | Use place-value strategies to subtract within 1,000 when a ten or a hundred is decomposed, and explain (orally) the strategy.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u7_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U7-L14",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 7 Lesson 14: Think Before You Subtract. The purpose of this lesson is for students to analyze expressions to determine if a unit will be decomposed before subtracting. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for subtracting a two-digit number from a three-digit number, based on place value. | Explain (orally) when one or more units will be decomposed when subtracting by place.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u7_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U7-L15",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 7 Lesson 15: Decompose a Ten and a Hundred to Subtract. The purpose of this lesson is for students to subtract 2 three-digit numbers, using strategies based on place value. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for subtracting 2 three-digit numbers that include decomposing two units. | Interpret (orally and using other representations) a written method for subtracting by place that includes decomposing two units.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u7_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U7-L16",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 7 Lesson 16: Subtract within 1,000. The purpose of this lesson is for students to choose methods for finding the values of differences, based on the numbers that are subtracted. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for subtracting within 1,000 based on place value or the properties of operations. | Interpret (orally) subtraction strategies based on place value and the properties of operations.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u7_l17, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U7-L17",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 7 Lesson 17: Does It Make Sense?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use strategies based on place value to decide if answers to story problems and the values they find when adding and subtracting make sense. Goals: Critique (orally and in writing) estimates made when problem solving and explain how to improve an estimate to make it more reasonable. | Explain (orally) estimation strategies for adding or subtracting within 1,000.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u7_l18, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U7-L18",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 7 Lesson 18: Center Day 3. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice adding and subtracting within 1,000. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding and subtracting within 1,000 based on place value.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u7_l19, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U7-L19",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 7 Lesson 19: Book Drive. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use addition and subtraction within 1,000 to organize information and answer questions about a book drive. Goals: Create (using words and other formats) a representation to organize information. | Explain (orally) how to use known information to solve real-world problems involving addition and subtraction.").
%   Unit 8
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u8_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U8-L1",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 8 Lesson 1: Can You Share?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to arrange a number of objects into 2 equal groups and learn that some numbers of objects can be put into 2 equal groups without any objects left over. Goals: Determine whether a collection of objects can be arranged into 2 equal groups with “some leftovers” or “no leftovers” and describe (orally) observations about each category.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u8_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U8-L2",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 8 Lesson 2: Partners Make Pairs. The purpose of this lesson is for students to pair all of the objects in a group and understand that some numbers of objects can be paired without any objects left over. Goals: Determine whether a collection of objects can be arranged into groups of 2 (or “pairs”) with “one leftover” or “no leftovers,” and describe (orally) observations about each category.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u8_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U8-L3",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 8 Lesson 3: Is It Odd or Even?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to determine whether representations of groups of objects show an even or odd number of objects. Goals: Comprehend (in written and spoken language) the meaning of the terms “even” and “odd.” | Explain (orally) strategies for determining whether images show an even or odd number of objects.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u8_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U8-L4",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 8 Lesson 4: Decompose Even and Odd Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent even numbers as the sum of two equal addends. Goals: Create equations with two addends that represent different ways to decompose even and odd numbers. | Generalize (orally) that even numbers can be represented as a sum of “two equal addends.”").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u8_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U8-L5",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 8 Lesson 5: Patterns with Even and Odd Numbers. The purpose of this optional lesson is for students to notice and describe patterns in sums within 20 using what they know about even and odd numbers. Goals: Describe (orally and in writing) patterns when counting by 1, and explain (orally) how to use these patterns to determine if a number is even or odd. | Generalize (orally) that adding 1 to a group changes whether it is even or odd but adding 2 does not.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u8_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U8-L6",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 8 Lesson 6: Center Day 1. The purpose of this lesson is for students to skip-count by 2, 5, and 10 and to add and subtract within 1,000. Goals: Choose to count by 2, 5, or 10 and record the numbers said when counting within 1,000.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u8_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U8-L7",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 8 Lesson 7: What Is an Array?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to learn that an array is an arrangement of objects into rows with an equal number of objects in each row. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the term “row” refers to objects arranged side to side and the term “array” refers to an arrangement of objects into “rows” with an equal number of objects in “each row.” | Create arrays and describe (orally) the rows of arrays.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u8_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U8-L8",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 8 Lesson 8: Count Columns and Objects in Columns. The purpose of this lesson is for students to see that in an array of objects, the objects are arranged into columns with an equal number of objects in each column. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the term “column” refers to objects arranged up and down in an array. | Create arrays and describe (orally) the “rows” and “columns” of arrays.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u8_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U8-L9",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 8 Lesson 9: A Sum of Equal Addends. The purpose of this lesson is for students to make connections between the structure of an array and expressions that represent the sum of the number of objects in each row or column in an array. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for finding the total number of objects in an array. | Match (orally) expressions with equal addends and arrays that represent the same value.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u8_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U8-L10",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 8 Lesson 10: Write Expressions and Equations to Represent Arrays. The purpose of this lesson is for students to write equations to show the sum of the rows or columns of an array. Goals: Create arrays and represent the objects in the array with an equation with equal addends.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u8_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U8-L11",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 8 Lesson 11: Arrays and Rectangles. The purpose of this lesson is for students to see that a rectangle partitioned into equal-size squares is composed of squares that are arranged in rows and columns. Goals: Create rectangles composed of square tiles and describe (orally) the rectangles using the language of arrays. | Draw to partition rectangles into an array of equal- size squares and explain (orally) how to determine the total number of equal-size squares that make up a rectangle.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u8_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U8-L12",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 8 Lesson 12: Partition Rectangles into Squares. The purpose of this lesson is for students to partition rectangles into equal-size squares. Goals: Describe (orally and using other representations) rectangles partitioned into equal-size squares using the language of arrays. | Explain (orally) strategies for partitioning rectangles into arrays of equal-size squares.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u8_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U8-L13",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 8 Lesson 13: Center Day 2. The purpose of this lesson is for students to skip-count by 2, 5, and 10 and to add and subtract within 1,000. Goals: Explain (orally) how to determine if equations with equal addends are true or false.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u8_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U8-L14",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 8 Lesson 14: A Band Concert. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use what they know about arrays to decide how to arrange chairs in a way that makes the most sense for a school concert. Goals: Choose an array to solve a real-world problem and justify (orally) the choice based on the constraints of the situation. | Create multiple arrays for a given number of objects.").
%   Unit 9
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u9_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U9-L1",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 9 Lesson 1: Sums and Differences within 20. The purpose of this lesson is for students to fluently add and subtract within 20 using mental strategies. Goals: Identify the value of sums and differences within 20 and explain (orally) mental strategies for identifying the value of sums and differences that are not yet known from memory.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u9_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U9-L2",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 9 Lesson 2: Fluency Flip. The purpose of this lesson is for students to fluently add and subtract within 20 to find unknown addends. Goals: Find an unknown addend and explain (orally) mental strategies.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u9_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U9-L3",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 9 Lesson 3: Measure on a Map. The purpose of this lesson is for students to measure lengths in centimeters and add and subtract lengths within 20 to answer questions. Goals: Represent Compare problems involving length using equations with a symbol for the unknown. | Use a ruler to measure the length of lines in centimeters and explain (orally) mental strategies for solving length problems within 20.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u9_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U9-L4",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 9 Lesson 4: Measure and Plot. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add and subtract within 20. Students measure lengths of objects and represent measurement data in line plots. Then they answer questions about the data. Goals: Create a line plot to represent measurement data and use line plots to ask and answer questions about measurement data. | Use a ruler to measure the length of objects in centimeters and explain (orally) how to use mental strategies to solve length problems within 20.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u9_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U9-L5",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 9 Lesson 5: Compose and Decompose Numbers within 1,000. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compose and decompose three-digit numbers in different ways. Goals: Explain (orally) how to compose or decompose units to represent a three-digit number in a different way. | Match (orally) words, numerals, expressions, and diagrams that represent the same three-digit number.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u9_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U9-L6",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 9 Lesson 6: Represent Numbers with Expressions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to demonstrate their understanding of place value by composing and decomposing numbers within 1,000 in different ways. Goals: Explain (orally) how to determine that an equation is true based on an understanding of composing and decomposing units. | Match (orally) expressions that represent the same value and use place value reasoning to create an expression with the same value.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u9_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U9-L7",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 9 Lesson 7: Add and Subtract within 1,000. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add and subtract within 1,000 using methods based on place value. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for finding the value of expressions within 1,000 that are more or less challenging. | Justify (orally and in writing) why sums and differences within 100 may be more or less challenging to find and explain mental strategies.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u9_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U9-L8",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 9 Lesson 8: Add and Subtract within 100. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice addition and subtraction within 100 to build fluency. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding and subtracting within 100.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u9_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U9-L9",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 9 Lesson 9: Sort the Story Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare, connect, and solve story problems. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) story problems. | Represent and solve one- and two-step story problems and compare and contrast (orally) the methods.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u9_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U9-L10",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 9 Lesson 10: What’s the Question?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to analyze a tape diagram and number line diagram and determine, in context, a question that could be answered based on each representation. Goals: Ask (orally and in writing) a question that can be answered based on given information. | Explain (orally) strategies for representing and solving story problems. | Interpret (orally and in writing) diagrams and equations that represent a solution to a story problem.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u9_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U9-L11",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 9 Lesson 11: All about Tape Diagrams. The purpose of this lesson is for students to make connections between story problems, equations, and tape diagrams. Goals: Create (in writing) and solve a story problem that represents the relationships shown in a tape diagram. | Match (orally) diagrams and equations that represent the same story problem.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u9_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U9-L12",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 9 Lesson 12: What’s the Story?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to ask mathematical questions and write story problems based on given equations. Goals: Create (in writing) and present (orally) a story problem. | Create (in writing) a story problem that represents the relationships shown in equations with an unknown addend.").
standard_anchor(im_grade2_u9_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G2-U9-L13",
    "IM Grade2 Unit 9 Lesson 13: Let’s Solve Our Story Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve story problems and represent their thinking. Goals: Represent and solve a story problem and present (using words or other representations) a strategy.").
% ─ grade3 ─
%   Unit 1
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u1_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U1-L1",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 1 Lesson 1: Make Sense of Data. The purpose of this lesson is to elicit students’ prior understandings of single-unit scale picture graphs and bar graphs in preparation for upcoming work with scaled bar graphs. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the meaning of the terms “key” and “scale.” | Interpret picture graphs and bar graphs and ask (orally and in writing) questions that can be answered by the data in a graph.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u1_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U1-L2",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 1 Lesson 2: Represent Data and Solve Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve one- and two-step problems about data represented in bar graphs. Goals: Explain (orally) how to use the features of a graph to solve one- and two-step Compare problems within 20. | Represent data using picture graphs and bar graphs.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u1_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U1-L3",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 1 Lesson 3: Scaled Picture Graphs. The purpose of this lesson is for students to read and answer questions about scaled picture graphs. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the meaning of the term “scaled picture graph.” | Interpret scaled picture graphs and ask questions (orally and in writing) about the data.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u1_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U1-L4",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 1 Lesson 4: Create Scaled Picture Graphs. The purpose of this lesson is for students to create a scaled picture graph to represent categorical data. Goals: Represent data using a scaled picture graph.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u1_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U1-L5",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 1 Lesson 5: Represent Data in Scaled Bar Graphs. The purpose of this lesson is for students to create a scaled bar graph. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally and in writing) bar graphs with different scales. | Comprehend (in spoken language) the meaning of the term “scaled bar graph.” | Represent data using a scaled bar graph.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u1_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U1-L6",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 1 Lesson 6: Choose a Scale. The purpose of this lesson is for students to consider the advantages and disadvantages of various bar graph scales. Goals: Represent data using a scaled bar graph and explain (orally) how a scale was chosen.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u1_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U1-L7",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 1 Lesson 7: Answer Questions about Scaled Bar Graphs. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve one-step “how many more?” and “how many fewer?” problems based on data presented in a scaled bar graph. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies used to solve one-step Compare problems within 100 based on data presented in scaled bar graphs. | Interpret scaled bar graphs and ask (in writing) questions that can be answered by the data in a scaled bar graph.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u1_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U1-L8",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 1 Lesson 8: More Questions about Scaled Bar Graphs. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve one- and two-step “how many more?” and “how many fewer?” problems based on data presented in a scaled bar graph. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving one- and two- step Compare problems. | Interpret (orally) a two-step Compare problem based on data presented in scaled bar graphs.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u1_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U1-L9",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 1 Lesson 9: Multiplication for Equal Groups. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use scaled picture graphs as an introduction to multiplication as a way to express equal groups. Goals: Describe (orally) how a drawing or diagram represents equal groups. | Represent a situation involving equal groups with drawings or diagrams.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u1_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U1-L10",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 1 Lesson 10: Situations, Drawings, and Diagrams, Oh My!. The purpose of this lesson is for students to connect situations involving equal groups to tape diagrams. Goals: Comprehend the term “multiplication” (in spoken language) refers to a way to represent the total number of objects when you have a certain number of equal groups. | Interpret a situation with equal groups and represent it with a drawing or diagram. | Match (orally and in writing)").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u1_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U1-L11",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 1 Lesson 11: Multiplication Expressions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use multiplication expressions to represent equal groups. Goals: Comprehend the notation ' ' can be used to create an expression to represent a number of equal groups. | Match (orally) situations, drawings, tape diagrams, and expressions that represent the same equal groups. | Represent situations involving equal groups with multiplication exp").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u1_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U1-L12",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 1 Lesson 12: Represent and Solve Multiplication Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent and solve multiplication problems. Goals: Represent and solve multiplication problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u1_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U1-L13",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 1 Lesson 13: Multiplication Equations. The purpose of this lesson is for students to relate multiplication equations to situations and diagrams and to write equations. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the meaning of the terms “factor” and “product.” | Match (orally) multiplication equations with situations, diagrams, and drawings. | Represent multiplication situations and diagrams with an equation.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u1_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U1-L14",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 1 Lesson 14: Write and Solve Equations with Unknowns. The purpose of this lesson is for students to relate equations to and write equations for multiplication situations and diagrams using a symbol for the unknown number. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for finding an unknown factor or product. | Match (orally) multiplication equations with a symbol for an unknown product or factor with situations and diagrams. | Represent a multiplication situation or diagram using an equation with a symbol for the u").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u1_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U1-L15",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 1 Lesson 15: More Factors, More Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve multiplication problems. Goals: Represent and solve multiplication problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u1_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U1-L16",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 1 Lesson 16: Arrange Objects into Arrays. The purpose of this lesson is for students to describe arrays and arrange objects into arrays. Goals: Create arrays and describe (orally) the relationship between objects arranged in an array and equal groups of objects.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u1_l17, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U1-L17",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 1 Lesson 17: Match and Draw Arrays. The purpose of this lesson is for students to relate arrays to drawings of equal groups and to describe arrays in terms of multiplication. Goals: Draw arrays to represent equal groups and describe (orally and in writing) the relationship between the arrays and multiplication. | Match (orally) arrays and drawings that represent the same equal groups.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u1_l18, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U1-L18",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 1 Lesson 18: Represent Arrays with Expressions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent multiplication situations with arrays and multiplication expressions. Goals: Represent multiplication situations using arrays and multiplication expressions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u1_l19, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U1-L19",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 1 Lesson 19: Solve Problems Involving Arrays. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent an array situation using an equation with a symbol for the unknown number and solve problems. Goals: Explain (orally) a strategy for representing and solving multiplication problems involving arrays. | Represent multiplication problems involving arrays using equations with a symbol for the unknown.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u1_l20, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U1-L20",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 1 Lesson 20: The Commutative Property. The purpose of this lesson is for students to describe the commutative property of multiplication using arrays. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) situations involving equal groups of rows and situations involving an equal group of columns. | Represent an array with different multiplication equations and explain (orally) how they each represent the array.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u1_l21, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U1-L21",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 1 Lesson 21: Game Night Seating Plan. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use their understanding of equal groups to solve a design problem. Goals: Present (using words and other representations) a representation of a real-world problem involving equal groups. | Represent data using a scaled bar graph.").
%   Unit 2
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u2_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U2-L1",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 2 Lesson 1: What Is Area?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to recognize that different shapes cover different amounts of space. Goals: Explain (orally) how to determine if a shape “covers the most space,” using informal tools and language.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u2_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U2-L2",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 2 Lesson 2: How Do We Measure Area?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use square tiles to build shapes and to measure area. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the term “area” as the amount of space covered by a shape. | Use square tiles to measure the area of a figure and express the area as a number of “square units.”").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u2_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U2-L3",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 2 Lesson 3: Tile Rectangles. The purpose of this lesson is for students to measure area by counting square tiles and to create rectangles with a given area. Goals: Comprehend the term “area” (in spoken and written language) as the number of square units that cover a flat figure with no gaps or overlaps. | Explain (orally and in writing) how to use square tiles without gaps or overlaps to measure the area of a rectangle (within 24 square uni").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u2_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U2-L4",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 2 Lesson 4: Area of a Rectangle. The purpose of this lesson is for students to continue to count squares to create rectangles and to find the areas of rectangles with greater numbers than in the previous lesson. Goals: Describe (orally) a gridded rectangle as an arrangement of unit squares in equal groups of rows and columns. | Explain (orally) strategies for finding the area of a gridded rectangle (within 60 square units).").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u2_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U2-L5",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 2 Lesson 5: Represent Products as Areas. The purpose of this lesson is for students to connect multiplication expressions to rectangular areas. Goals: Draw and label on a gridded rectangle to represent a multiplication expression. Relate the area of the rectangle and the value of the expression. | Match (orally) gridded rectangles and multiplication expressions that represent the same equal groups.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u2_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U2-L6",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 2 Lesson 6: Different Square Units (Part 1). The purpose of this lesson is for students to learn that there are different units that can be used to measure area, specifically the square centimeter and the square inch. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and in written language) the meaning of the terms “square inch” and “square centimeter.” | Use square inches and square centimeters to measure the area of a rectangle.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u2_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U2-L7",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 2 Lesson 7: Different Square Units (Part 2). The purpose of this lesson is for students to learn about the square foot and the square meter, and consider when these larger units can be helpful to measure area. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and in written language) the meaning of the terms “square foot” and “square meter.” | Explain (orally and in writing) whether a given area would be measured with square centimeters, square inches, square feet, or square meters.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u2_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U2-L8",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 2 Lesson 8: Area of a Rectangle without a Grid. The purpose of this lesson is for students to determine the areas of rectangles that are not fully gridded with squares. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for finding the area of a partially-gridded rectangle. | Generalize (orally) strategies for finding the area of any rectangle given the side lengths.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u2_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U2-L9",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 2 Lesson 9: Measure to Find the Area. The purpose of this lesson is for students to measure side lengths of rectangles to find their areas. Goals: Explain (orally) how to use a ruler to find the area of a rectangle.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u2_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U2-L10",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 2 Lesson 10: Solve Area Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve problems involving area. Goals: Present (using words and other representations) strategies used to represent and solve real-world problems involving area.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u2_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U2-L11",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 2 Lesson 11: Area and the Multiplication Table. The purpose of this lesson is for students to explore connections between area and the multiplication table. Goals: Describe (orally and in writing) patterns in the products on a multiplication table, and justify why they happen. | Describe (orally) the relationship between the area of a gridded rectangle and the representation of a product on the multiplication table.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u2_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U2-L12",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 2 Lesson 12: Area and Addition. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use gridded rectangles to learn that area is additive. Goals: Explain (orally) a strategy for finding the area of a gridded figure composed of rectangles. | Present (using words or other representations) a strategy for finding the area of a gridded “figure” composed of rectangles.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u2_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U2-L13",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 2 Lesson 13: Find the Area of a Figure. The purpose of this lesson is for students to calculate the area of ungridded figures made of rectangles, using multiplication and addition. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for calculating the area of ungridded figures composed of rectangles.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u2_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U2-L14",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 2 Lesson 14: Find the Area of a Figure with Unknown Side Lengths. The purpose of this lesson is for students to calculate the areas of ungridded figures made of rectangles, including figures with unknown side lengths. Goals: Critique (orally and in writing) a strategy for calculating an unknown side length. | Explain (orally) strategies for calculating the area of a figure composed of rectangles, including figures with unknown side lengths.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u2_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U2-L15",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 2 Lesson 15: New Room. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use their experience with areas of figures composed of rectangles to solve problems. Goals: Explain (orally) decisions and assumptions made when representing and solving a real-world problem. | Present (using words and other representations) a solution to a real-world problem involving the areas of figures, including those with unknown side lengths.").
%   Unit 3
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u3_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U3-L1",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 3 Lesson 1: Represent Numbers in Different Ways. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent numbers, using base-ten blocks, base-ten diagrams, expanded form, numerals, and word form. Goals: Match (orally) base-ten diagrams, expressions, number names, and three-digit numbers that represent the same value. | Represent ways to decompose the same three-digit number, using expressions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u3_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U3-L2",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 3 Lesson 2: Addition and Subtraction Situations. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use addition and subtraction to solve problems within 1,000. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving addition and subtraction problems within 1,000.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u3_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U3-L3",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 3 Lesson 3: Add Your Way. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use strategies to add within 1,000. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) addition strategies based on place value. | Explain (orally) strategies for adding within 1,000.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u3_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U3-L4",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 3 Lesson 4: Introduction to Addition Algorithms. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use their knowledge of base-ten diagrams to make sense of two written addition algorithms. Goals: Comprehend (in written and spoken language) the meaning of the term “algorithm.” | Interpret addition algorithms and use an algorithm to calculate sums within 1,000.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u3_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U3-L5",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 3 Lesson 5: Another Addition Algorithm. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use an addition algorithm that records a single digit for the sum of each place-value position, and “10” or “100” for a newly composed ten or hundred, respectively. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) addition algorithms and explain how they work using place value understanding.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u3_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U3-L6",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 3 Lesson 6: Use Strategies and Algorithms to Add. The purpose of this lesson is for students to record newly composed tens and hundreds with a single digit and to consider when they might use algorithms or other strategies to add. Goals: Describe (orally) how addition algorithms represent composed units. | Explain (orally) strategies for finding sums within 1,000, including algorithms or other relevant methods.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u3_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U3-L7",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 3 Lesson 7: Subtract Your Way. The purpose of this lesson is to activate the strategies students have for subtracting numbers within 1,000. Goals: Explain (using words and other representations) strategies for subtracting within 1,000. | Interpret (orally) base-ten diagrams that represent decomposing units and subtracting by place.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u3_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U3-L8",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 3 Lesson 8: Subtraction Algorithms (Part 1). The purpose of this lesson is for students to use their knowledge of base-ten diagrams to make sense of a written subtraction algorithm. Goals: Interpret (orally and in writing) the steps of a written subtraction algorithm. | Match (orally) base-ten diagrams and algorithms that represent the same subtraction strategy.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u3_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U3-L9",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 3 Lesson 9: Subtraction Algorithms (Part 2). The purpose of this lesson is for students to subtract within 1,000, using a subtraction algorithm that records numbers in expanded form. Goals: Describe (orally and in writing) work showing an error in a subtraction algorithm. | Use a subtraction algorithm with the numbers written in expanded form.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u3_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U3-L10",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 3 Lesson 10: Subtraction Algorithms (Part 3). The purpose of this lesson is for students to use a subtraction algorithm that records a single digit for the difference between the numbers in each place-value position and a condensed notation for a decomposed hundred or ten. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally and in writing) subtraction algorithms. | Explain (orally) how to use an algorithm to subtract.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u3_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U3-L11",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 3 Lesson 11: Analyze Subtraction Algorithms. The purpose of this lesson is for students to consider subtraction algorithms in more detail, with a focus on decomposing as needed and on cases when it is necessary to decompose multiple units to subtract across zeros. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally and in writing) subtraction algorithms. | Use and explain (orally) subtraction algorithms.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u3_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U3-L12",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 3 Lesson 12: Subtract Strategically. The purpose of this lesson is for students to consider when they might use algorithms or other strategies to subtract. Goals: Subtract within 1,000 and explain (orally) how a strategy was chosen based on the numbers in the expression.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u3_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U3-L13",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 3 Lesson 13: Multiples of 100. The purpose of this lesson is for students to reason about the positions of numbers relative to their immediate multiples of 100, using number lines to do so. Goals: Comprehend (in written and spoken language) that the phrase “nearest multiple of 100” refers to the multiple of 100 that is closest to a number. | Explain (orally) how to decide whether or not a number is close to 0, 100, or 200. | Explain (orally) how to use a number line to ide").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u3_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U3-L14",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 3 Lesson 14: Nearest Multiples of 10 and of 100. The purpose of this lesson is for students to reason about the positions of numbers relative to their immediate multiples of 10 and multiples of 100, using number lines to do so. Goals: Comprehend (in written and spoken language) the phrase “nearest multiple of 10” refers to the multiple of 10 that is closest to a number. | Explain (orally and in writing) how to determine the nearest multiple of 10 and the nearest multiple of 100.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u3_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U3-L15",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 3 Lesson 15: Round to the Nearest Ten and the Nearest Hundred. The purpose of this lesson is for students to round whole numbers within 1,000 to the nearest ten or the nearest hundred. Goals: Comprehend (in written and spoken language) what it means to “round” a number. | Round whole numbers within 1,000, and describe (orally and in writing) observations about the same number rounded to the nearest ten and the nearest hundred.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u3_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U3-L16",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 3 Lesson 16: Round and Round Again. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use their understanding of rounding to consider all the numbers that round to a given number. Goals: Describe (orally) a three-digit number including details based on rounding to the nearest ten or hundred. | Determine (in writing) all the numbers that can round to a given multiple of 10 or multiple of 100, and describe (orally) observed patterns.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u3_l17, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U3-L17",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 3 Lesson 17: Does It Make Sense?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use mental computation and estimation strategies, such as rounding to decide if answers to two-step word problems make sense. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) how to determine if an estimate for a solution to a word problem is reasonable. | Solve two-step word problems, using addition and subtraction.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u3_l18, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U3-L18",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 3 Lesson 18: Diagrams and Equations for Word Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to relate diagrams and equations to two-step word problems. Goals: Match (orally and in writing) two-step word problems, tape diagrams, and equations that represent the same relationships. | Present (using words and other representations) a strategy for solving a two-step word problem.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u3_l19, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U3-L19",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 3 Lesson 19: Situations and Equations. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent and solve two-step word problems. Goals: Match (orally) tape diagrams, equations, and two- step word problems that represent the same relationships. | Represent and solve two-step word problems, using equations with a letter standing for the unknown quantity.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u3_l20, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U3-L20",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 3 Lesson 20: More Practice to Represent and Solve. The purpose of this lesson is for students to continue to represent and solve two-step word problems, including problems for which not all necessary information is given up front. Goals: Determine the information needed to solve one- and two-step word problems. Ask (orally and in writing) questions to elicit that information.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u3_l21, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U3-L21",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 3 Lesson 21: Classroom Supplies. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use their understanding of estimation, rounding, and addition within 1,000 to solve a problem about a class wish list. Goals: Calculate the difference between quantities and describe (orally) comparisons, using “more” and “less.” | Use and explain (orally) estimation or rounding strategies to solve a real-world problem.").
%   Unit 4
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L1",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 1: How Many Groups?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve “how many groups?” problems in a way that makes sense to them. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) strategies for solving “how many groups?” problems. | Explain (using words or other representations) strategies for solving “how many groups?” problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L2",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 2: How Many in Each Group?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve “how many in each group?” problems in a way that makes sense to them. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) strategies for solving “how many in each group?” word problems. | Explain (using words or other representations) strategies for solving “how many in each group?” problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L3",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 3: Division Situation Drawings. The purpose of this lesson is for students to interpret descriptions or drawings of division situations and recognize whether they involve finding an unknown number of groups or finding an unknown number of objects in each group. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the meaning of the term “division.” | Match (orally) diagrams and division word problems that represent the same relationship.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L4",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 4: Interpret Division Expressions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to interpret division expressions and understand that the same division expression can be used to represent both types of division situations. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the meaning of the term “divisor.” | Comprehend the notation can be used to create an expression to represent division. | Match (orally) word problems, diagrams, and division expressions that represent the same relationship.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L5",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 5: Write Division Expressions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to write division expressions to represent division situations and solve “how many groups?” and “how many in each group?” problems. Goals: Present (using words and other representations) a strategy for solving a “how many groups?” or “how many in each group?” problem. | Represent division situations using division expressions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L6",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 6: Division as an Unknown Factor. The purpose of this lesson is for students to relate multiplication and division and to recognize division as an unknown factor problem. Goals: Interpret (orally) a multiplication equation with an unknown factor and a division equation that represent the same word problem. | Represent division situations with drawings or diagrams, multiplication equations, and division equations. Describe (orally) the relationships betwe").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L7",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 7: Relate Multiplication and Division. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use the relationship between multiplication and division to write equations and solve problems. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving word problems that involve equal groups. | Represent situations with equal groups using drawings, word problems, multiplication equations, and division equations.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L8",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 8: Relate Quotients to Familiar Products. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice identifying multiplication facts within 100 and to use products they know to determine unknown quotients. Goals: Create division equations that share a relationship with known multiplication facts. | Explain (orally) strategies for calculating the value of multiplication expressions that are not yet known facts.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L9",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 9: Patterns in the Multiplication Table. The purpose of this lesson is for students to identify and explain patterns in the multiplication table. Goals: Explain (orally) how to use patterns in the multiplication table to determine unknown products.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L10",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 10: Explore Multiplication Strategies with Rectangles. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use area diagrams to explore multiplication strategies based on properties of operations. Goals: Explain (orally) how to label gridded rectangles and write expressions to represent decomposing the area of a rectangle into parts. | Interpret (orally) gridded rectangles and expressions that represent strategies based on properties of multiplication.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L11",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 11: Multiplication Strategies on Ungridded Rectangles. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent multiplication strategies on an ungridded rectangle. Goals: Label ungridded rectangles and explain (orally) strategies based on properties of operations for calculating the area of each rectangle. | Match (orally) expressions that represent the area of the same rectangle, including those that show the associative and distributive properti").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L12",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 12: Multiply Multiples of 10. The purpose of this lesson is for students to multiply one-digit numbers by multiples of 10. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for multiplying one-digit numbers by multiples of 10, including using place- value understanding to decompose one of the factors. | Explain (orally) strategies for solving word problems involving multiplying one-digit numbers by multiples of 10.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L13",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 13: Solve Problems with Equal Groups. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve problems involving multiplication within 100, where one factor is a teen number, in a way that makes sense to them. Goals: Compare and contrast (using words and other representations) strategies for representing and solving multiplication problems within 100, where one factor is a teen number.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L14",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 14: Ways to Represent Multiplication of Teen Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to make sense of representations of the multiplication of teen numbers. Goals: Interpret (orally and in writing) diagrams and expressions that represent strategies for multiplication where one factor is a teen number.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L15",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 15: Equal Groups, Greater Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to multiply within 100, where one factor is a teen number. Goals: Compare and contrast (using words and other representations) strategies for representing and solving a multiplication problem within 100 that involves area.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L16",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 16: Multiply Numbers Greater than 20. The purpose of this lesson is for students to multiply within 100, where one factor is greater than 20. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for multiplying within 100, where one factor is greater than 20, including strategies based on place value and properties of operations. | Interpret (orally) base-ten diagrams and area diagrams that represent multiplication within 100, where one factor").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l17, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L17",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 17: Use the 4 Operations to Solve Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve two-step problems using all four operations. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving two-step word problems using any of the four operations. | Represent two-step word problems using equations with a letter standing for the unknown quantity.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l18, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L18",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 18: Greater Numbers in Equal Groups. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve problems involving division within 100, with quotients greater than 10, in a way that makes sense to them. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving “how many groups?” and “how many in each group” problems within 100, with quotients greater than 10.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l19, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L19",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 19: Ways to Divide Greater Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to recognize that the two interpretations of division still apply when dividing greater numbers and to use base-ten diagrams to interpret and represent division within 100. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for division where the quotient is greater than 10. | Interpret (orally and in writing) a base-ten diagram that shows finding the number of groups and a base- ten diagram that shows finding the size of each group for the same division expression.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l20, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L20",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 20: Strategies for Dividing. The purpose of this lesson is for students to analyze representations and strategies for finding quotients with greater numbers and to divide within 100. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally and in writing) strategies used to represent and calculate the same quotient. | Explain (orally) strategies for dividing within 100.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l21, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L21",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 21: Solve Problems Using the Four Operations. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent and solve two-step word problems using the four operations. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving two-step word problems using any of the four operations. | Represent two-step word problems using equations with a letter standing for the unknown quantity.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u4_l22, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U4-L22",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 4 Lesson 22: School Community Garden. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use multiplication and division to model a real-world design problem. Goals: Match (orally) expressions and diagrams that are used to represent the same multiplication and division problems in a real-world context. | Present (using words and other representations) a design for a real-world problem that involves solving two-step problems and follows given").
%   Unit 5
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u5_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U5-L1",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 5 Lesson 1: Name the Parts. The purpose of this lesson is to introduce students to fractions as numbers that describe equal parts of a whole. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) that the term “partition” refers to splitting a shape into parts. | Explain (orally) how to partition shapes into 2, 3, 4, 6, or 8 equal parts. | Identify (orally and in writing) equal parts as “halves,” “thirds,” “fourths,” “sixths,” a").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u5_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U5-L2",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 5 Lesson 2: Name Parts as Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to partition shapes into equal parts and to express each equal-size part as a unit fraction. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the term “fraction,” and that the notation can be used to represent unit fractions. | Draw and label to partition shapes into halves, thirds, fourths, sixths, and eighths. Express the size of each part as a unit fraction").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u5_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U5-L3",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 5 Lesson 3: Non-unit Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to understand non-unit fractions. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the meaning of the term “unit fraction.” | Generalize (orally) that a fraction   refers to a quantity of   parts of size   .").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u5_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U5-L4",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 5 Lesson 4: Build Fractions from Unit Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to build non-unit fractions and whole numbers from unit fractions. Goals: Justify (orally) that a non-unit fraction has the same value as a number of unit fractions. | Represent (using diagrams) a word problem involving non-unit fractions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u5_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U5-L5",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 5 Lesson 5: To the Number Line. The purpose of this lesson is for students to extend their understanding of whole numbers on the number line as they work with number lines partitioned into fractions. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for locating and labeling unit fractions on number lines that represent numbers within 1.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u5_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U5-L6",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 5 Lesson 6: Locate Unit Fractions on the Number Line. The purpose of this lesson is for students to partition the interval from 0 to 1, and to locate unit fractions within that interval. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for locating and labeling unit fractions on number lines, including those that represent numbers greater than 1.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u5_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U5-L7",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 5 Lesson 7: Non-unit Fractions on the Number Line. The purpose of this lesson is for students to locate non-unit fractions on the number line. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the meaning of the terms “numerator” and “denominator.” | Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for locating and labeling non-unit fractions (including fractions greater than 1) on the number line.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u5_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U5-L8",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 5 Lesson 8: Fractions and Whole Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to recognize fractions that are equivalent to whole numbers, and to locate whole numbers on the number line when given the location of a unit fraction. Goals: Describe (orally) patterns in fractions that are at the same location as whole numbers on the number line. | Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for locating and labeling whole numbers on the number line when given a unit fraction.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u5_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U5-L9",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 5 Lesson 9: All Kinds of Numbers on the Number Line. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use their knowledge of fractions on the number line to locate 1 when given a non-unit fraction. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for locating and labeling 1 on the number line when given a non- unit fraction, and critique (orally) explanations of strategies.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u5_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U5-L10",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 5 Lesson 10: Equivalent Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to see that different fractions can be equivalent if they are the same size of the same-size whole. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the term “equivalent fractions.” | Explain (orally) how to determine if diagrams represent equivalent fractions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u5_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U5-L11",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 5 Lesson 11: Generate Equivalent Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to generate equivalent fractions. Goals: Explain (orally) how to use a diagram to determine two equivalent fractions. | Use diagrams to identify and generate (orally and in writing) equivalent fractions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u5_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U5-L12",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 5 Lesson 12: Equivalent Fractions on a Number Line. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use the number line to determine whether fractions are equivalent. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the term “equivalent fractions.” | Generate (orally and in writing) equivalent fractions. | Use a number line to justify (orally and in writing) that two or more fractions are equivalent.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u5_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U5-L13",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 5 Lesson 13: Whole Numbers and Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to recognize fractions that are equivalent to whole numbers and write whole numbers as fractions. Goals: Generate (orally and in writing) fractions that are equivalent to a whole number, and describe (orally) observed patterns. | Use a number line to generate (orally and in writing) fractions that are equivalent to whole numbers, and to determine if a fraction is equivalent to a who").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u5_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U5-L14",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 5 Lesson 14: How Do You Compare Fractions?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent and compare fractions in a way that makes sense to them. Goals: Critique (orally and in writing) strategies for comparing fractions. | Explain (using words and other representations) strategies for determining if two fractions are equivalent.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u5_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U5-L15",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 5 Lesson 15: Compare Fractions with the Same Denominator. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare two fractions with the same denominator. Goals: Explain (with words or other representations) strategies for comparing fractions with the same denominator. | Express a comparison of two fractions, using >, <, or =.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u5_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U5-L16",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 5 Lesson 16: Compare Fractions with the Same Numerator. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare two fractions with the same numerator. Goals: Explain (with words or other representations) strategies for comparing fractions with the same numerator.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u5_l17, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U5-L17",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 5 Lesson 17: Compare Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare two fractions with the same numerator or the same denominator in and out of context, and to justify their conclusions. Goals: Determine (orally and in writing) the numerator, denominator, or fraction that makes a comparison statement true. | Explain (using words or other representations) strategies for comparing fractions with the same numerator or the same denominator.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u5_l18, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U5-L18",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 5 Lesson 18: Plan a Fun Run. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply their understanding of fractions to plan a 3-mile fun run. Goals: Explain (orally) decisions and assumptions made when representing and solving a real-world problem. | Interpret (orally and in writing) symbols on a map that represent fractional lengths. | Present (using words and other representations) a design for a real-world problem involvin").
%   Unit 6
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u6_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U6-L1",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 6 Lesson 1: Measure in Halves of an Inch. The purpose of this lesson is for students to measure lengths that are fractions of an inch and relate these measurements to fractions on a number line. Goals: Explain (orally) how to measure objects with a ruler marked with halves of an inch and express measurements to the nearest half-inch.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u6_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U6-L2",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 6 Lesson 2: Measure in Fourths of an Inch. The purpose of this lesson is for students to measure length using a ruler marked with fourths of an inch. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the meaning of the term “mixed number.” | Use rulers marked with fourths of an inch to measure objects and express measurements to the nearest half- and quarter-inch as fractions and mixed numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u6_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U6-L3",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 6 Lesson 3: Measure in Halves and Fourths of an Inch. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use what they know about fraction equivalence to measure with a ruler that is marked with halves and fourths of an inch. Goals: Use a ruler marked with both halves and fourths of an inch to measure objects and express measurements using equivalent fractions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u6_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U6-L4",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 6 Lesson 4: Interpret Measurement Data on Line Plots. The purpose of this lesson is for students to make sense of line plots that represent measurements to the nearest half or fourth of an inch. Goals: Ask (orally and in writing) questions that can be answered by a line plot. | Interpret (orally and in writing) line plots that display measurement data in fractions of an inch.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u6_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U6-L5",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 6 Lesson 5: Represent Measurement Data on Line Plots. The purpose of this lesson is for students to generate measurement data and represent them on a line plot. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) line plots that include measurements to the nearest half-inch or quarter- inch. | Present (using words and other representations) a line plot marked off in appropriate units—whole numbers, halves, or quarters—to represent collected measurement data.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u6_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U6-L6",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 6 Lesson 6: Estimate and Measure Weight. The purpose of this lesson is for students to learn to measure and estimate the weight of objects in grams or kilograms. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the terms “weight,” “gram,” and “kilogram.” | Explain (orally) strategies for estimating the weights of objects in kilograms and grams.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u6_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U6-L7",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 6 Lesson 7: Introduction to Liquid Volume. The purpose of this lesson is to introduce students to the measurement of liquid volume. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the terms “volume of a liquid,\" “volume of a container,” and “liter.” | Explain (orally) how to estimate, measure, and compare the volume of containers using informal units and liters.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u6_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U6-L8",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 6 Lesson 8: Estimate and Measure Liquid Volume. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use liters to measure and estimate liquid volumes. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for estimating the volumes of containers in liters. | Interpret (orally) the measurement scale on diagrams representing the volume of a liquid and draw to represent a given volume.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u6_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U6-L9",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 6 Lesson 9: Time to the Nearest Minute. The purpose of this lesson is for students to tell and write time to the nearest minute. Goals: Determine (orally and in writing) the time shown on an analog clock to the nearest minute. | Represent a given time to the nearest minute on an analog clock face.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u6_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U6-L10",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 6 Lesson 10: Solve Problems Involving Time (Part 1). The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve problems involving addition and subtraction of time intervals in minutes in a way that makes sense to them. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for representing and solving elapsed-time problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u6_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U6-L11",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 6 Lesson 11: Solve Problems Involving Time (Part 2). The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve problems involving addition and subtraction of time intervals in minutes. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving elapsed-time problems with the unknown in all positions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u6_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U6-L12",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 6 Lesson 12: Ways to Represent Measurement Situations. The purpose of this lesson is for students to make sense of situations involving measurements, interpret representations of the situations, and ask and answer questions about them. Goals: Ask (orally and in writing) and answer questions about real-world situations involving measurements. | Match (orally and in writing) tape diagrams and word problems involving measurements that represent the same relationships.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u6_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U6-L13",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 6 Lesson 13: Problems with Missing Information. The purpose of this lesson is for students to determine the information needed to solve problems involving weight. Goals: Determine the information needed to solve measurement problems involving addition, subtraction, multiplication, or division. Ask (orally) questions to elicit that information.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u6_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U6-L14",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 6 Lesson 14: What Makes Sense in the Problem?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to consider quantities and questions that make sense in situations and solve problems accordingly. Goals: Interpret (orally) equations and diagrams that represent strategies for solving problems involving measurement. | Represent and solve one-step word problems involving time and liquid volume.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u6_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U6-L15",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 6 Lesson 15: Ways to Solve Problems and Show Solutions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve problems using the four operations as they imagine spending a day at the fair. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally and in writing) strategies for solving problems involving measurements. | Present (using words or other representations) strategies for solving problems involving measurements and equal groups.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u6_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U6-L16",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 6 Lesson 16: Design a Game. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply their understanding of length measurement, time measurement, and fluency with four operations to design a game. Goals: Describe (orally) revisions made to a game based on testing and new constraints. | Explain (orally and in writing) the rules to a game and justify the decisions made when designing it.").
%   Unit 7
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u7_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U7-L1",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 7 Lesson 1: What Attributes Do You See?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to sort shapes into categories based on their attributes. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the phrases “angle in a shape” and “right angle in a shape.” | Describe (orally) the attributes of shapes using formal or informal language.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u7_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U7-L2",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 7 Lesson 2: Attributes of Triangles and Quadrilaterals. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use attributes of triangles and quadrilaterals to sort them into more specific categories. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the phrases “equal side lengths” or “equal sides” refer to 2 or more sides with the same length measurement. | Describe (orally) the attributes of subcategories of triangles and quadrilaterals.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u7_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U7-L3",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 7 Lesson 3: Attributes that Define Shapes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to describe geometric attributes of shapes. Goals: Describe (orally) and identify shapes using their distinguishing attributes.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u7_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U7-L4",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 7 Lesson 4: Attributes of Rectangles, Rhombuses, and Squares. The purpose of this lesson is for students to consider the geometric attributes a quadrilateral must have to be a rectangle, rhombus, or square. Goals: Comprehend (in written and spoken language) the meaning of the terms “rhombus,” “rectangle,” and “square.” | Describe (orally and in writing) and identify rhombuses, squares, and rectangles based on their defining attributes.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u7_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U7-L5",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 7 Lesson 5: Attributes of Other Quadrilaterals. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use their knowledge of geometric attributes to name quadrilaterals in different ways and to draw quadrilaterals that are not rhombuses, rectangles, or squares. Goals: Draw quadrilaterals that are non-examples of rhombuses, rectangles, and squares. | Generalize that shapes can belong to more than one category.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u7_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U7-L6",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 7 Lesson 6: Distance around Shapes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to understand perimeter and find the perimeter of shapes by counting to determine the side lengths. Goals: Comprehend (in written and spoken language) the meaning of the term “perimeter.” | Explain (orally) a strategy for calculating the perimeter of a shape.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u7_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U7-L7",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 7 Lesson 7: Same Perimeter, Different Shapes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice finding the perimeter of shapes and to understand that many different shapes can have the same perimeter. Goals: Determine and draw examples of different shapes with the same perimeter.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u7_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U7-L8",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 7 Lesson 8: Find the Perimeter. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find perimeters of shapes given all or some of the side lengths. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) strategies for calculating the perimeter of shapes given all the side lengths. | Explain (using words and other representations) strategies for calculating the perimeter of a shape given its attributes and some side lengths.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u7_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U7-L9",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 7 Lesson 9: Perimeter Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find unknown side lengths given the perimeter of a shape and solve problems involving perimeter. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for calculating an unknown side length given the perimeter of a shape. | Explain (orally) strategies for solving word problems involving perimeter.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u7_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U7-L10",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 7 Lesson 10: Problem Solving with Perimeter and Area. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve problems that involve both perimeter and area of rectangles in order to reinforce the difference between perimeter and area. Goals: Determine the information needed to solve two-step word problems involving the area and perimeter of rectangles. Ask (orally) questions to elicit that information. | Solve problems that involve perimeter and area of rectangles.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u7_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U7-L11",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 7 Lesson 11: Rectangles with the Same Perimeter. The purpose of this lesson is for students to understand that rectangles with the same perimeter do not always have the same area. Goals: Draw rectangles with a given perimeter and different areas.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u7_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U7-L12",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 7 Lesson 12: Rectangles with the Same Area. The purpose of this lesson is for students to understand that rectangles with the same area do not always have the same perimeter. Goals: Draw rectangles with the same area and different perimeters.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u7_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U7-L13",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 7 Lesson 13: Shapes and Play. The purpose of this lesson is for students to consider how geometric attributes, perimeter, and area are used when designing a playground. Goals: Draw and describe (orally) a design for a real-world rectangular space using constraints related to area and perimeter.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u7_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U7-L14",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 7 Lesson 14: Wax Prints. The purpose of this lesson is for students to consider how geometric attributes, perimeter, and area are used to design and use wax print fabric. Goals: Create and describe (orally) a design made from quadrilaterals that follows given constraints. | Determine the information needed to solve two-step word problems involving area and perimeter. Ask (orally) questions to elicit that information.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u7_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U7-L15",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 7 Lesson 15: A Space for Chickens. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use what they know about area and perimeter to solve problems. Goals: Present (using words and other representations) a design for a real-world problem involving area and perimeter that meets given constraints.").
%   Unit 8
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u8_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U8-L1",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 8 Lesson 1: Estimation Explorations with Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice reasoning about fraction representations through estimation. Goals: Determine (orally and in writing) estimates of fractions represented in diagrams and on number lines that are “too low,” “about right,” and “too high.”").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u8_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U8-L2",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 8 Lesson 2: Create Your Own Number Line. The purpose of this lesson is for students to create their own number line to represent and compare fractions. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for locating and labeling whole numbers, unit fractions, and non-unit fractions on the number line. | Express comparisons of fractions and whole numbers, using >, <, and =.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u8_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U8-L3",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 8 Lesson 3: Fractions Round Table. The purpose of this lesson is for students to consider statements about fractions that will help them solidify their understanding of fractions as numbers. Goals: Critique (orally) statements and generalizations about fractions, whole numbers represented as fractions, and fraction comparisons.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u8_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U8-L4",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 8 Lesson 4: Tiny House: Design and Solve. The purpose of this lesson is for students to design and solve problems about a tiny house. Goals: Ask (orally and in writing) and answer questions about the area and the perimeter of a rectangular floor plan partitioned into smaller areas. | Present (in words and other representations) a design for a rectangular floor plan that follows given constraints.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u8_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U8-L5",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 8 Lesson 5: Tiny House: Cost. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply what they’ve learned about operations to calculate the cost to finish a space in a tiny house. Goals: Present (in words and other representations) strategies for solving real-world, multi-step addition word problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u8_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U8-L6",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 8 Lesson 6: Survey the Class, Survey the School. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use a survey to collect a data set with several categories. Goals: Create a survey, and collect and organize a data set with several categories.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u8_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U8-L7",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 8 Lesson 7: Graph and Answer. The purpose of this lesson is for students to draw a scaled bar graph to represent a data set with several categories. Goals: Create (orally and in writing) and solve one- and two- step Compare problems, based on data presented in a scaled bar graph. | Represent collected data, with a scaled bar graph, and explain (orally) how a scale was chosen.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u8_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U8-L8",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 8 Lesson 8: Multiplication Center Day. The purpose of this lesson is for students to evaluate their fluency with multiplication within 100. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for comparing two multiplication expressions, including those that do not involve calculating the values of the products. | Explain (orally) strategies for determining the values of multiplication expressions that are not yet known facts.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u8_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U8-L9",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 8 Lesson 9: Multiplication Game Day. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice multiplying within 100. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies used to multiply within 100 when playing multiplication games.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u8_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U8-L10",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 8 Lesson 10: Multiplication and Division. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use a variety of representations to illustrate the relationship between multiplication and division as a means to develop fluency with division within 100. Goals: Create and present (using words and other representations) division equations, diagrams, and word problems that represent the same relationships. | Match (orally) division equations and diagrams or multiplication equations with an unknown factor that represent the same equal grou").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u8_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U8-L11",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 8 Lesson 11: Division Game Day. The purpose of this lesson is for students to develop fluency with dividing within 100. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for comparing two division expressions, including those that do not involve calculating the values of the quotients. | Explain (orally) strategies for dividing within 100.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u8_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U8-L12",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 8 Lesson 12: Notice and Wonder. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply their understanding of equal groups to create a Notice and Wonder routine. Goals: Create (in writing) and present a Notice and Wonder routine involving equal groups.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u8_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U8-L13",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 8 Lesson 13: How Many Do You See?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply their understanding of equal groups and multiplication to create a How Many Do You See? routine. Goals: Create (in writing) and present a How Many Do You See? routine involving equal groups.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u8_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U8-L14",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 8 Lesson 14: Estimation Exploration. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply their understanding of measurement of fractional lengths to create an Estimation Exploration routine. Goals: Create (in writing) and present an Estimation Exploration routine involving lengths to the nearest half or fourth of an inch.").
standard_anchor(im_grade3_u8_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G3-U8-L15",
    "IM Grade3 Unit 8 Lesson 15: Number Talk. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply their understanding of addition and subtraction to create a Number Talk routine. Goals: Create a Number Talk routine. | Describe (orally) how a set of expressions are related.").
% ─ grade4 ─
%   Unit 1
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u1_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U1-L1",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 1 Lesson 1: Multiples of a Number. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply their understanding of area to explore multiples. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the meaning of the phrase “multiple of a number.” | Create (using other representations) rectangles given a side length and determine their area.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u1_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U1-L2",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 1 Lesson 2: Factor Pairs. The purpose of this lesson is for students to learn the meaning of factor pairs by building rectangles with a specified area. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the meaning of the term “factor pair.” | Create (using words and other representations) and describe (orally) the possible rectangles with whole- number side lengths given an area.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u1_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U1-L3",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 1 Lesson 3: Prime and Composite Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to identify factor pairs and determine whether a given whole number in the range 1–100 is prime or composite. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the terms “prime number” and “composite number.” | Determine the factor pairs of a given whole number 1–100. | Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for determining whether a given whole number is prime or composite.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u1_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U1-L4",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 1 Lesson 4: Multiplication Practice. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice multiplication within 100. Goals: Determine the factor pairs of a given number within 40. | Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for determining products that are not yet known facts.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u1_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U1-L5",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 1 Lesson 5: More Multiples. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use multiples of single-digit numbers to solve real-world problems. This includes situations with multiple solutions and situations with no solutions. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for solving real-world problems that involve factors and multiples within 100.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u1_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U1-L6",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 1 Lesson 6: The Locker Problem. The purpose of this lesson is for students to examine factors of numbers from 1 to 20 and use them to solve problems. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for representing and solving problems that involve factors, multiples, prime numbers, and composite numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u1_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U1-L7",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 1 Lesson 7: Find Factors and Multiples. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find factors and multiples of a given whole number from 1–100. Goals: Justify (orally and in writing) that a number is a factor of another number. | Justify (orally and in writing) that a number is a multiple of another number.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u1_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U1-L8",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 1 Lesson 8: Mondrian's Art. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply their understanding of the area of rectangles and factor pairs to create and analyze Mondrian-inspired art. Goals: Create artwork composed of rectangles that follows constraints related to factors, multiples, prime numbers, and composite numbers. | Describe (orally) how artwork represents given constraints related to factors, multiples, prime numbers, and composite numbers.").
%   Unit 2
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u2_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U2-L1",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 2 Lesson 1: Representations of Fractions (Part 1). The purpose of this lesson is for students to make sense of unit fractions with denominators 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 8, 10, and 12, using physical and visual representations. Goals: Describe (orally and in writing) the relationship between the denominator and the size of the unit fraction. | Represent and identify unit fractions that have denominators 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 8, and 12 on physical and visual representations.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u2_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U2-L2",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 2 Lesson 2: Representations of Fractions (Part 2). The purpose of this lesson is for students to make sense of non-unit fractions (including those greater than 1) that have denominators 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 8, 10, and 12. Goals: Explain (orally) how to determine what non-unit fraction is represented by a tape diagram. | Represent a non-unit fraction on a tape diagram.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u2_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U2-L3",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 2 Lesson 3: Same Denominator or Numerator. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use the meaning of a fraction's numerator and denominator and to compare fractions with the same numerator or the same denominator. Goals: Describe (orally) characteristics of the numerators or denominators when comparing fractions with the same numerator or same denominator. | Explain (orally) strategies for comparing fractions with the same numerator or same denominator, including using physical or visual represen").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u2_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U2-L4",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 2 Lesson 4: Same Size, Related Sizes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use visual representations to reason about the fractions that have the same size and to locate them on the number line. Goals: Describe (orally) the relationship between fractions in which one denominator is the multiple of another (for example,    and   ). | Explain (orally) strategies for locating fractions on the number line. | Justify (orally) that two fractions are equivalent if they have the same s").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u2_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U2-L5",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 2 Lesson 5: Fractions on Number Lines. The purpose of this lesson is for students to recognize that equivalent fractions describe the same point on the number line and to identify such fractions on a number line. Goals: Justify (orally and using other representations) that two fractions are equivalent if they are on the same point on a number line. | Label equivalent fractions on number line diagrams.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u2_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U2-L6",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 2 Lesson 6: Relate Fractions to Benchmarks. The purpose of this lesson is for students to locate fractions on the number line and compare their size to         and to 1. Goals: Justify (using words or other representations) that a fraction is greater than or less than   or 1.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u2_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U2-L7",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 2 Lesson 7: Equivalent Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to generate equivalent fractions using a representation that makes sense to them. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) strategies for generating equivalent fractions. | Explain (orally) strategies for generating equivalent fractions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u2_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U2-L8",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 2 Lesson 8: Equivalent Fractions on the Number Line. The purpose of this lesson is for students to reason about and generate equivalent fractions on the number line. Goals: Explain (orally and using other representations) how to generate equivalent fractions using a number line.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u2_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U2-L9",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 2 Lesson 9: Explain Equivalence. The purpose of this lesson is for students to determine if two fractions are equivalent, and if they are, explain why they are equivalent. Goals: Justify (orally and using other representations) that a pair of given fractions are equivalent.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u2_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U2-L10",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 2 Lesson 10: Use Multiples to Find Equivalent Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to make sense of a way to identify and generate equivalent fractions by using multiples of the numerator and denominator. Goals: Explain (orally) how to use multiples of the numerator and denominator to generate equivalent fractions. | Match (orally) equations and number line diagrams that represent strategies for generating equivalent fractions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u2_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U2-L11",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 2 Lesson 11: Use Factors to Find Equivalent Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to generate equivalent fractions numerically, by using factors and multiples of the numerator and denominator. Goals: Explain (orally and using words or other representations) how to generate equivalent fractions. | Match (orally) equations and number line diagrams that represent strategies for generating equivalent fractions by reasoning about division.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u2_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U2-L12",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 2 Lesson 12: Ways to Compare Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare fractions in a way that makes sense to them, including by reasoning about the size of fractional parts, common numerators or denominators, or relationships to benchmarks such as       an Goals: Explain (orally and using words or other representations) strategies for comparing fractions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u2_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U2-L13",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 2 Lesson 13: Use Equivalent Fractions to Compare. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare two fractions by rewriting one of them as an equivalent fraction with the same denominator as the other. Goals: Determine whether a fraction is greater than, less than, or equivalent to another fraction and express the comparison using >, <, or =. | Explain (orally and using words or other representations) strategies for comparing fractions, including reasoning about equivalent fractions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u2_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U2-L14",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 2 Lesson 14: Fraction Comparison Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare fractions to solve problems in and out of context. Goals: Explain (orally and using words or other representations) strategies for solving fraction comparison problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u2_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U2-L15",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 2 Lesson 15: Use Common Denominators to Compare. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare two fractions with different denominators by rewriting both as an equivalent fraction with a common denominator. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the term “common denominator.” | Generate equivalent fractions for a pair of fractions based using common denominators. | Interpret (orally) strategies for comparing two fractions based on rewriting both fractions as equi").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u2_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U2-L16",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 2 Lesson 16: Compare and Order Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare and order fractions using any strategy. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for comparing and ordering fractions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u2_l17, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U2-L17",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 2 Lesson 17: Paper Clip Games. The purpose of this lesson is for students to create and play a game about locating and comparing fractions on a number line. Goals: Determine (orally) the location of an object on a representation of a number line. | Present (in writing and using other representations) a game that includes constraints related to fraction concepts and vocabulary.").
%   Unit 3
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u3_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U3-L1",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 3 Lesson 1: Equal Groups of Unit Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to interpret and relate descriptions, drawings, and multiplication expressions that represent equal groups of unit fractions. Goals: Interpret (orally and in writing) situations involving equal groups of fractions. | Represent situations involving equal groups of fractions, with multiplication expressions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u3_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U3-L2",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 3 Lesson 2: Representations of Equal Groups of Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to interpret and generate diagrams and expressions that represent the multiplication of a whole number and a unit fraction in order to find the value of the product. Goals: Interpret (orally and in writing) diagrams and expressions that represent multiplication of a whole number and a unit fraction. | Use diagrams and expressions to represent and determine the product of a whole number and a unit fraction.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u3_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U3-L3",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 3 Lesson 3: Patterns in Multiplication. The purpose of this lesson is for students to understand that every fraction can be written as the product of a whole number and a unit fraction. Goals: Explain (orally) that           , using an understanding of equal groups. | Represent a non-unit fraction as a product of a whole number and a unit fraction.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u3_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U3-L4",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 3 Lesson 4: Equal Groups of Non-unit Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is to apply understandings from previous lessons to multiply a non-unit fraction by a whole number. Goals: Describe (orally) patterns in the products of whole numbers and non-unit fraction. | Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for determining the product of a whole number and a non-unit fraction.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u3_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U3-L5",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 3 Lesson 5: Equivalent Multiplication Expressions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to write equivalent expressions for the multiplication of a whole number and a unit fraction, and explain the equivalence. Goals: Generate multiplication expressions that represent a given fraction. | Justify (using words or other representations) that multiplication expressions involving whole numbers and fractions are equivalent.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u3_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U3-L6",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 3 Lesson 6: Problems with Equal Groups of Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply their understanding of multiplication of a fraction by a whole number to solve problems. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving problems involving multiplication of a fraction and a whole number. | Represent situations involving multiplication of a fraction and a whole number, with expressions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u3_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U3-L7",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 3 Lesson 7: Fractions as Sums. The purpose of this lesson is for students to decompose, in more than one way, a fraction into a sum of fractions with the same denominator, and to write an equation for each decomposition. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for representing a non-unit fraction as a sum of fractions with the same denominator. | Generate addition expressions that represent decomposing a non-unit fraction.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u3_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U3-L8",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 3 Lesson 8: Addition of Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use a number line to reason about addition of fractions with the same denominator, and to decompose fractions greater than 1 into a whole number and a fraction less than 1. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the meaning of the term “mixed number.” | Represent a fraction greater than 1 as a sum of a whole number and a fraction less than 1. | Use the number line to represent sums of fractions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u3_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U3-L9",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 3 Lesson 9: Differences of Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use a number line to reason about subtraction of fractions with the same denominator. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for using a number-line diagram to subtract fractions. | Interpret (orally) number-line diagrams that represent a subtraction strategy.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u3_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U3-L10",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 3 Lesson 10: The Numbers in Subtraction. The purpose of this lesson is for students to recognize that a fraction can be subtracted from a whole number by writing an equivalent fraction for the whole number. It also can be done by decomposing the whole number, the fraction, or both Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for subtracting a fraction from a whole number.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u3_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U3-L11",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 3 Lesson 11: Subtract Fractions Flexibly. The purpose of this lesson is for students to subtract fractions, including mixed numbers, by decomposing numbers and writing equivalent fractions, and to recognize when these strategies are useful for finding differences. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for solving problems involving subtraction of fractions and mixed numbers. | Interpret (orally) expressions that represent subtracting fractions and mixed numbers by decomposing numbers and reasoning about equivalence.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u3_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U3-L12",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 3 Lesson 12: Sums and Differences of Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to consider strategies for adding and subtracting fractions with the same denominator, including mixed numbers, and to recognize when it is helpful to decompose numbers or to write equivalent fract Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for adding and subtracting fractions, including mixed numbers. | Justify (orally) whether or not it is necessary or helpful to decompose a number when adding or subtracting fractions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u3_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U3-L13",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 3 Lesson 13: Fractional Measurements on Line Plots. The purpose of this lesson is for students to display a set of measurements in fractions of a unit ( ,      , and   ) on a line plot, and then interpret the data. Students also add and subtract fractions to answer questions about data prese Goals: Create line plots to represent collected measurement data in fractions of a unit (       ). | Interpret (orally and in writing) fractional measurement data on line plots.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u3_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U3-L14",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 3 Lesson 14: Problems about Fractional Measurement Data. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve problems, using information presented in line plots. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for solving problems involving addition and subtraction of fractions and mixed numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u3_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U3-L15",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 3 Lesson 15: An Assortment of Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use equivalence to reason about problems that involve combining or removing fractional amounts. Goals: Explain (using words or other representations) strategies for comparing the height of objects composed of different unit fractions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u3_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U3-L16",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 3 Lesson 16: Add Tenths and Hundredths Together. The purpose of this lesson is for students to write equivalent fractions to add tenths and hundredths, up to a sum of 1. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for adding tenths and hundredths.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u3_l17, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U3-L17",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 3 Lesson 17: Sums of Tenths and Hundredths. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use equivalent fractions to add tenths and hundredths, when the sum is greater than 1. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for determining the number that makes an equation with tenths and hundredths true. | Justify (orally) that an addition expression with tenths and hundreds is greater than, less than, or equal to 1.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u3_l18, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U3-L18",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 3 Lesson 18: A Lot of Fractions to Add. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find the sum of three or more tenths and hundredths. Goals: Determine the sum of three or more tenths and hundredths.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u3_l19, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U3-L19",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 3 Lesson 19: Flexible with Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to interpret and solve problems that involve adding, subtracting, and multiplying fractions. Goals: Interpret (orally) and solve multi-step problems that involve the addition, subtraction, and multiplication of fractions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u3_l20, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U3-L20",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 3 Lesson 20: Sticky Notes. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply their understanding of multiplication of a whole number by a fraction to create sticky-note letter designs. Goals: Ask (orally) questions to gather information to improve an estimate. | Create a design that follows constraints, based on lengths that include fractions.").
%   Unit 4
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L1",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 1: Decimal Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to make sense of tenths and hundredths in decimal notation. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the term “decimal notation.” | Interpret (orally) tenths and hundredths expressed in decimal notation. | Represent tenths and hundredths using decimal notation.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L2",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 2: Equivalent Decimals. The purpose of this lesson is for students to reason about equivalent tenths and hundredths in decimal notation. Goals: Determine (orally) whether 2 ways of expressing tenths and hundredths are equivalent. | Match (orally) diagrams and decimals that represent the same value.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L3",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 3: Decimals on Number Lines. The purpose of this lesson is for students to reason about and compare the size of decimals using a number line. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for comparing decimals to hundredths and express comparisons using >, <, =.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L4",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 4: Compare and Order Decimals. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare and order decimals. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for comparing and ordering decimals.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L5",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 5: Compare and Order Decimals in Different Notations. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare and order fractions and decimals to the hundredths. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for comparing and ordering decimals.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L6",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 6: How Much Is 10,000?. The purpose of this lesson is to develop a relative sense of ten-thousand and understand it as a unit consisting of 10 units of one-thousand. Goals: Explain (orally) how to represent thousands and ten- thousands using base-ten blocks or diagrams. | Represent 5-digit numbers with base-ten blocks and diagrams.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L7",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 7: Numbers Within 100,000. The purpose of this lesson is to read, write, and represent multi-digit numbers up to the ten-thousands. Goals: Determine the number of thousands and ten- thousands represented by a 5-digit number. | Write 5-digit numbers and express 5-digit numbers with words.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L8",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 8: Beyond 100,000. The purpose of this lesson is to read, write, and represent numbers within 1,000,000 using base-ten blocks, diagrams, and expanded form. Goals: Interpret (orally and in writing) representations with base-ten blocks for whole numbers within 1,000,000. | Represent whole numbers within 1,000,000 using base-ten blocks, diagrams, numerals, words, and equations.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L9",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 9: Same Digit, Different Value. The purpose of this lesson is to describe the value of a digit in one place as having ten times the value of the same digit in a place to its right. Goals: Describe (orally and in writing) that the value of a digit in one place represents “ten times” what it represents in the place to its right.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L10",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 10: Ten Times As Much. The purpose of this lesson is to write equations to represent the relationship between the value of digits in multi-digit numbers. Goals: Use equations to express the relationship between the value of a digit and its value in the place to its right.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L11",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 11: Large Numbers on a Number Line. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use place value understanding to locate large numbers on a number line and describe number relationships in which one multi-digit number is ten times as much as another. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for estimating the location of multi-digit whole numbers on a number line diagram.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L12",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 12: Compare Multi-Digit Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare two multi-digit whole numbers within 1,000,000 by reasoning about place value and to explain how they make comparisons. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for comparing 2 multi-digit whole numbers within 1,000,000.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L13",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 13: Order Multi-Digit Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to compare and order multi-digit whole numbers within 1,000,000. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies based on place value for comparing and ordering multi-digit whole numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L14",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 14: Multiples of 10,000 and 100,000. The purpose of this lesson is for students to reason about the position of numbers relative to their multiples of 1,000, 10,000, and 100,000. Goals: Use a number line diagram to identify (orally and in writing) the closest multiples of 1,000, 10,000, and 100,000 to a given whole number.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L15",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 15: The Nearest Multiples of 1,000, 10,000, and 100,000. The purpose of this lesson is for students to determine the nearest multiple of 1,000, 10,000, and 100,000 and a given multi-digit whole number. Goals: Determine the nearest multiple of 1,000, 10,000, and 100,000 given a multi-digit whole number.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L16",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 16: Round Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to round multi-digit whole numbers within 1,000,000 to the nearest thousand, ten-thousand, and hundred-thousand. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for rounding multi-digit whole numbers to the nearest thousand, ten- thousand, and hundred-thousand.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l17, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L17",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 17: Apply Rounding. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use rounding to learn about situations and solve problems involving multi- digit whole numbers within 1 million. Goals: Describe (orally) situations where rounding can help or hinder problem-solving. | Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for solving problems involving rounding multi-digit numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l18, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L18",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 18: Standard Algorithm to Add and Subtract. The purpose of this lesson is to add and subtract large numbers within 100,000 using the standard algorithm. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) written methods for adding and subtracting multi-digit numbers. | Comprehend (in spoken language) the meaning of the term “standard algorithm.” | Use the standard algorithm to add and subtract (without decomposing) multi-digit numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l19, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L19",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 19: Compose and Decompose to Add and Subtract. The purpose of this lesson is for students to review how to add and subtract multi-digit numbers with composition and decomposition. Goals: Interpret (orally) recording methods for showing composed and decomposed units. | Use the standard algorithm to add and subtract multi-digit numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l20, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L20",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 20: Add and Subtract within 1,000,000. The purpose of this lesson is for students to add and subtract within 1,000,000 with multiple compositions or decompositions. Goals: Determine (orally and in writing) errors made when adding or subtracting using the standard algorithm. | Use the standard algorithm to add and subtract multi-digit numbers with multiple compositions or decompositions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l21, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L21",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 21: Zeros in the Standard Algorithm. The purpose of this lesson is to use the standard algorithm when the minuend has several zeros. Goals: Interpret (orally) written methods that use the standard algorithm to subtract when the minuend has several zeros. | Use the standard algorithm to subtract within 100,000 when the minuend has several zeros.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l22, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L22",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 22: Solve Problems Involving Large Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve problems that involve adding and subtracting multi-digit numbers. Goals: Interpret (orally) and solve problems that involve determining sums and differences of multi-digit whole numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u4_l23, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U4-L23",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 4 Lesson 23: Bees are Buzzing. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use estimation to make sense of a wide range of numbers and to use addition and subtraction to investigate how an insect population can change over time. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving problems that involve adding and subtracting multi-digit whole numbers. | Interpret (orally) multi-digit whole numbers in a real- world context.").
%   Unit 5
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u5_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U5-L1",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 5 Lesson 1: Times as Many. The purpose of this lesson is for students to interpret and represent multiplicative comparison situations, using objects and diagrams. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) that the phrase “ times as many” refers to number of groups of an original quantity. | Represent multiplicative comparison situations, using objects and drawings.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u5_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U5-L2",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 5 Lesson 2: Interpret Representations of Multiplicative Comparison. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent situations and descriptions of multiplicative comparison, using diagrams and equations. Goals: Match (orally) situations, diagrams, and equations that represent the same multiplicative comparison. | Use diagrams to represent and solve multiplicative comparison problems in which the greater quantity is unknown.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u5_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U5-L3",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 5 Lesson 3: Solve Multiplicative Comparison Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to interpret and represent multiplicative comparison situations in which a factor is unknown. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for representing and solving multiplicative comparison problems that involve finding an unknown multiplier or lesser quantity.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u5_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U5-L4",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 5 Lesson 4: Solve Multiplicative Comparison Problems with Large Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to extend their understanding of multiplicative comparison to situations that involve larger quantities and larger multipliers. Goals: Interpret (orally and in writing) diagrams that represent multiplicative comparison problems with greater quantities. | Represent multiplicative comparison problems with equations and diagrams, and solve the problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u5_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U5-L5",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 5 Lesson 5: One- and Two-Step Comparison Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve multiplicative comparison word problems with one or two steps. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for representing and solving two-step problems involving multiplicative comparison.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u5_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U5-L6",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 5 Lesson 6: Ten Times as Many. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent and solve multiplicative comparison problems involving multiples of 10. Goals: Describe (orally) the relationship between a lesser quantity and a greater quantity that is “10 times as many.” | Interpret (orally and in writing) diagrams that represent a multiplicative comparison involving “10 times as many.”").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u5_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U5-L7",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 5 Lesson 7: Meters and Centimeters. The purpose of this lesson is for students to make sense of the relative sizes of meters and centimeters and to express meters in terms of centimeters. Goals: Describe (orally and in writing) a meter as 100 times the length of a centimeter. | Determine a measurement in centimeters that is equivalent to a measurement in meters.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u5_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U5-L8",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 5 Lesson 8: Meters and Kilometers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to describe the multiplicative relationship between kilometers and meters, and to express the former in terms of the latter. Goals: Describe (orally) a kilometer as 1,000 times the length of a meter. | Determine a measurement in meters that is equivalent to a measurement in kilometers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u5_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U5-L9",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 5 Lesson 9: Grams and Kilograms, Liters, and Milliliters. The purpose of this lesson is for students to describe the relationship between kilograms and grams, and between liters and milliliters, and to express each of the larger units in terms of the smaller units. Goals: Describe (orally) the multiplicative relationships between kilograms and grams, and liters and milliliters. | Determine a measurement in grams that is equivalent to a measurement in kilograms. | Determine a measurement in milliliters that is equivalent to a measurement in liters.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u5_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U5-L10",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 5 Lesson 10: Multi-Step Measurement Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply what they learned about metric units of measurement and multiplicative comparison to solve multi-step problems. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving problems that involve metric measurements, with whole numbers and multiplicative comparison.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u5_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U5-L11",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 5 Lesson 11: Pounds and Ounces. The purpose of this lesson is for students to make sense of the relative sizes of pounds and ounces, and to express pounds in terms of ounces. Goals: Describe (orally and in writing) a pound as 16 times as heavy as an ounce. | Determine a measurement in ounces that is equivalent to a measurement in pounds.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u5_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U5-L12",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 5 Lesson 12: Hours, Minutes, and Seconds. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use multiplication to describe the relationship between units of time and to express larger units of time in terms of smaller ones. Goals: Describe (orally) the multiplicative relationships between units of time. | Determine a measurement in minutes that is equivalent to a measurement in hours. | Determine a measurement in seconds that is equivalent to a measurement in minutes.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u5_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U5-L13",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 5 Lesson 13: Multi-Step Measurement Problems with Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve multi-step problems that involve multiplicative comparison and measurement in whole numbers and fractions. Goals: Determine the information needed to solve problems that involve multiplicative comparison and measurement with whole numbers and fractions. Ask (orally) questions to elicit that information.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u5_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U5-L14",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 5 Lesson 14: Weight and Capacity Measurements. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply their understanding of multiplicative comparison and unit conversion to solve multi-step problems about weight and about capacity. Goals: Describe (orally) the multiplicative relationships between customary units of capacity (gallons, quarts, cups). | Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for solving multi-step problems about units of weight and capacity.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u5_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U5-L15",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 5 Lesson 15: Length Measurements. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply their understanding of multiplicative comparison and unit conversion to solve multi-step problems about distances and lengths. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for solving multi-step problems about units of length (yards, feet, inches).").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u5_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U5-L16",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 5 Lesson 16: Compare Perimeters of Rectangles. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply multiplicative reasoning and their knowledge of fractions to solve problems about perimeters of rectangles. Goals: Determine the perimeter and the side lengths of rectangles. | Use multiplication to compare the perimeters of rectangles.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u5_l17, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U5-L17",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 5 Lesson 17: More Perimeter Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve geometric problems, using their understanding of length measurements, unit conversion, multiplicative comparison, and addition or subtraction of fractions. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving problems involving perimeter that include multiplicative comparison and addition and subtraction of fractions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u5_l18, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U5-L18",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 5 Lesson 18: Two Truths and a Lie. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply their understanding of multiplicative comparison and measurement conversion to compare facts about animals. Goals: Create (in writing) multiplicative comparison statements using an understanding of units of measurement. | Justify (orally) whether a multiplicative comparison statement is true or false.").
%   Unit 6
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L1",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 1: Patterns that Grow. The purpose of this lesson is for students to generate visual patterns and identify and informally explain any features that were not explicit in the given rule. Goals: Describe (orally) features in a growing shape pattern that were not explicit in a given rule. | Determine (orally and using other representations) the next steps in a growing shape pattern given a rule.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L2",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 2: Patterns that Repeat. The purpose of this lesson is for students to generate repeating shape patterns that follow given rules, explain apparent features that were not explicit in the rules, and use those features and what they know about properties of operations Goals: Create a repeating shape pattern given a rule | Describe (orally and in writing) features in a repeating shape pattern that were not explicit in a given rule. | Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for predicting later terms in a repeating visual pattern.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L3",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 3: Numerical Patterns. The purpose of this lesson is for students to generate numerical patterns given a rule and explain apparent features of the pattern that were not explicit in the rule. Goals: Create a numerical pattern given a rule involving addition. | Describe (orally and in writing) features in a numerical pattern that were not explicit in the rule. | Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for predicting later terms in a numerical pattern.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L4",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 4: More Numerical Patterns. The purpose of this lesson is for students to, given a rule, generate numerical patterns and use their understanding of place value and properties of operations to explain features of the pattern that were not explicit in the rule. Goals: Create a numerical pattern given a rule involving multiplication. | Use place value and properties of operations to describe (orally and in writing) features in a numerical pattern that were not explicit in the rule.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L5",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 5: Products Beyond 100. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find the product of a one-digit number and a two-digit number in ways that make sense to them. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for solving problems that involve multiplying two-digit by one- digit whole numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L6",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 6: Multiply Two-Digit Numbers and One-Digit Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to multiply a two-digit number and a one-digit number using place value understanding. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the meaning of the term “partial products.” | Interpret (orally and in writing) diagrams that represent partial products as a strategy for multiplying two-digit and one-digit whole numbers. | Represent products of two-digit and one-digit numbers wi").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L7",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 7: Multiply Three- and Four-Digit Numbers by One-Digit Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to multiply a whole number of up to four digits by a one-digit number by decomposing factors by place value, finding partial products, and using properties of operations. Goals: Interpret (orally and in writing) diagrams that represent a partial product as a strategy for multiplying three- and four-digit numbers by place. | Represent products of three- or four-digit and one- digit numbers with a diagram and calculate the value.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L8",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 8: Multiply 2 Two-Digit Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to multiply 2 two-digit numbers. Goals: Describe (orally) how decomposing factors by place value is helpful when determining products. | Use a diagram to multiply 2 two-digit numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L9",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 9: Recording Partial Products: One-Digit and Three- or Four-Digit Factors. The purpose of this lesson is for students to multiply a multi-digit number by a one-digit number using an algorithm that uses partial products. Students make connections between this algorithm, rectangular diagrams, and equations. Goals: Interpret and use an algorithm that uses partial products to multiply multi-digit whole numbers by one-digit numbers. | Match diagrams and recording methods that represent the same multiplication strategy.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L10",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 10: Using Algorithms with Partial Products: 2 Two-Digit Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use partial products in an algorithm to multiply 2 two-digit numbers. Goals: Interpret (orally and in writing) an algorithm that uses partial products to multiply 2 two-digit numbers. | Use an algorithm that uses partial products to multiply 2 two-digit numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L11",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 11: Partial Products and the Standard Algorithm. The purpose of this lesson is for students to analyze the standard algorithm for multiplication and compare it to an algorithm that uses partial products they saw in earlier lessons. Goals: Calculate the product of three- or four-digit numbers and one-digit numbers. | Compare and contrast (orally and in writing) algorithms that use partial-products, including the standard algorithm for multiplication").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L12",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 12: Solve Problems Involving Multiplication. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve contextual problems that involve multiplication of a single-digit number and a whole number of up to four digits, or multiplication of 2 two-digit numbers. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for solving problems that involve multiplication of multi-digit numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L13",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 13: Situations Involving Equal-Size Groups. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve division problems in context, both those that ask “how many in each group” and those that ask “how many groups,” in a way that makes sense to them. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for solving “how many in each group” and “how many groups” problems within 100. | Interpret (orally) division equations that represent “how many in each group” and “how many groups” problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L14",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 14: Situations Involving Area. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve division problems that involve tiling squares and finding a side length of a rectangle with a known area in a way that makes sense to them. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) strategies for solving area problems with two- and three-digit numbers and an unknown side length.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L15",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 15: Base-Ten Blocks to Divide. The purpose of this lesson is for students to make sense of base-ten representations for division. Goals: Explain (orally) how to use base-ten blocks to represent and calculate the division of a two-digit number by a one-digit divisor.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L16",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 16: Base-Ten Diagrams to Represent Division. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find the quotients of two-digit and three-digit dividends and one-digit divisors as they consider base-ten diagrams that represent the problems. Goals: Interpret (orally) methods for division based on place-value. | Use base-ten blocks or diagrams to divide two- or three-digit numbers by one-digit divisors.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l17, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L17",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 17: An Algorithm with Partial Quotients. The purpose of this lesson is to introduce students to ways to record partial quotients when dividing multi-digit numbers. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the meaning of the term “partial quotients.” | Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for dividing three-digit numbers by one-digit numbers. | Interpret (orally and in writing) recording methods for division that uses partial quotients.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l18, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L18",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 18: Use an Algorithm with Partial Quotients. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use an algorithm with partial quotients to find whole number quotients with up to four-digit dividends and one-digit divisors. Goals: Determine (orally and in writing) computation errors when dividing four-digit numbers by one-digit divisors and explain how to correct the errors. | Use an algorithm with partial quotients to divide up to four-digit numbers by one-digit divisors.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l19, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L19",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 19: Divide with Remainders. The purpose of this lesson is to introduce division expressions that have remainders. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the term “remainder.” | Explain (orally) strategies for dividing up to four-digit numbers by one-digit divisors. | Interpret (orally) the quotient and remainder for a situation involving division.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l20, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L20",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 20: Interpret Remainders in Division Situations. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent and solve contextual problems that involve dividing a whole number of up to four-digits by a single-digit divisor, resulting in a number with or without a remainder. Students also inte Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for solving problems that involve interpreting a remainder. | Interpret (orally and in writing) the quotient and remainder for a situation involving division.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l21, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L21",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 21: Problems with Remainders. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply their understanding of division, multiplication, factors, and multiples to solve problems involving remainders. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for determining whether a number is a multiple or factor of another.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l22, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L22",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 22: Different Ways to Solve Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent and solve multi-step contextual problems involving multiplication and division, including division with remainders. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for solving multi-step problems involving unknown products and unknown factors.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l23, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L23",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 23: Problems about Perimeter and Area. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply what they know about multiplication and division to convert units of measurement and solve multi-step problems involving perimeter and area. Goals: Explain (orally and using words or other representations) strategies for solving multi-step problems involving measurement conversions, perimeter, and area.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l24, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L24",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 24: Solve Problems with Many Operations. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use the four operations to solve problems involving multi-digit numbers. Students also use the standard algorithm for addition and subtraction to solve problems. For each problem, students asses Goals: Explain (orally and using words or other representations) strategies for solving multi-step problems involving up to 6-digit whole numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l25, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L25",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 25: Assess the Reasonableness of Solutions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve multi-step word problems by analyzing data, estimating, reasoning, and performing multiple operations. It also helps students to build fluency in using the standard algorithm to add and su Goals: Explain (orally and using words or other representations) strategies for solving multi-step problems. | Explain (orally) a strategy for determining whether an answer is reasonable.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u6_l26, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U6-L26",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 6 Lesson 26: Paper Flower Decorations. The purpose of this lesson is for students to create patterns and solve multi-step problems. Goals: Create a work plan that follows constraints related to operations with multi-digit whole numbers. | Explain (orally) strategies for making reasonable assumptions when solving a problem.").
%   Unit 7
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u7_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U7-L1",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 7 Lesson 1: How Would You Describe These Figures?. The purpose of this lesson is to motivate the need for geometric language for describing and drawing images and to introduce points, lines, and segments. Goals: Describe (orally and in writing) geometric figures, using “point,” “line,” and “line segment” informally.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u7_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U7-L2",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 7 Lesson 2: Points, Lines, Rays, and Segments. The purpose of this lesson is for students to identify and draw lines, segments, and rays. Goals: Determine (orally) defining characteristics of lines, line segments, points, and rays. | Draw line segments and rays.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u7_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U7-L3",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 7 Lesson 3: Two or More Lines. The purpose of this lesson is for students to identify and draw parallel and intersecting lines. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the terms “intersecting lines” and “parallel lines.” | Explain (orally and in writing) how to determine if lines are intersecting or parallel.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u7_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U7-L4",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 7 Lesson 4: Points and Lines All Around. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice identifying parallel and intersecting lines and drawing them. Goals: Draw figures with parallel and intersecting lines. | Identify (orally and in writing) parallel and intersecting lines in figures and drawings.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u7_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U7-L5",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 7 Lesson 5: What Is an Angle?. The purpose of this lesson is to introduce angles and to motivate a need for vocabulary to describe what they are and their sizes. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the term “angle.” | Identify (orally and in writing) angles in two- dimensional figures.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u7_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U7-L6",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 7 Lesson 6: Compare and Describe Angles. The purpose of this lesson is for students to consider ways to compare angles and describe the size of an angle. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally and in writing) angles.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u7_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U7-L7",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 7 Lesson 7: The Size of an Angle on a Clock. The purpose of this lesson is for students to describe the size of an angle as the amount of turn of one ray away from the other. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the “size of angle” as the amount of turn one ray makes from another ray that is fixed at the same starting point. | Use the features of an analog clock to describe (orally), and compare the sizes of angles.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u7_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U7-L8",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 7 Lesson 8: The Size of An Angle, in Degrees. The purpose of this lesson is for students to understand that angles can be measured in degrees and to use benchmark angle measurements to make sense of the new unit. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the term “degree.” | Use parts of a circle (halves, fourths) and benchmark angle measurements (such as 90°, 180°, 270°, 360°) to estimate the size of an angle, in degrees.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u7_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U7-L9",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 7 Lesson 9: Use a Protractor to Measure Angles. The purpose of this lesson is for students to understand   as a measurement of a turn through        of a circle, and to use a protractor to measure angles. Goals: Describe (orally and in writing) that 1 degree is a turn through a full circle. | Explain (orally) how to use a protractor to measure the size of an angle.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u7_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U7-L10",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 7 Lesson 10: Angle Measurement and Perpendicular Lines. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice using a protractor to measure angles and to learn that intersecting lines that create 4 right angles are perpendicular lines. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of “perpendicular lines.” | Identify (orally) and draw perpendicular lines.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u7_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U7-L11",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 7 Lesson 11: Use a Protractor to Draw Angles. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use a protractor to draw angles of given measurements. Goals: Use a protractor to draw angles of given measurements.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u7_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U7-L12",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 7 Lesson 12: Types of Angles. The purpose of this lesson is for students to classify angles as acute, obtuse, and straight, and to identify and draw acute and obtuse angles. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the terms \"acute angle,\" \"obtuse angle,\" \"right angle,\" and \"straight angle.\" | Identify acute, obtuse, right, and straight angles in two-dimensional figures.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u7_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U7-L13",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 7 Lesson 13: Find Angle Measurements. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find unknown angle measurements by composing or decomposing known measurements, and to see that an angle is not determined by the lengths of the segments that form it. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for determining the size of an angle, based on composing and decomposing angles.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u7_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U7-L14",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 7 Lesson 14: Reasoning about Angles (Part 1). The purpose of this lesson is twofold: for students to use known angles to reason about unknown angles on a clock, and for them to practice drawing angles of given measurements. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for determining the size of an angle within a circle.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u7_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U7-L15",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 7 Lesson 15: Reasoning about Angles (Part 2). The purpose of this lesson is to use known angles to reason about unknown angles and to write equations to reason about unknown angles. Goals: Determine the information needed to solve a problem with an unknown angle measurement. Ask (orally) questions to elicit that information. | Represent angle relationships, with an equation, using a symbol for an unknown angle measurement, and calculate an unknown angle measurement").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u7_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U7-L16",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 7 Lesson 16: Angles, Streets, and Steps. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply what they have learned about the measurement of angles to solve real-world problems. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for representing and solving problems involving angle measurement.").
%   Unit 8
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u8_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U8-L1",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 8 Lesson 1: Ways to Look at Figures. The purpose of this lesson is for students to analyze flat figures and sort them into different categories based on their attributes. Goals: Determine (orally and in writing) the shared attributes of a group of two-dimensional shapes. | Match (orally and in writing) two-dimensional shapes based on a shared attribute.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u8_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U8-L2",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 8 Lesson 2: Ways to Look at Triangles. The purpose of this lesson is for students to classify triangles based on their side lengths and the size of their angles. Students identify triangles with a right angle as right triangles. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) how to determine if a triangle is a right triangle. | Match (orally and in writing) triangles based on the size of their angles, length of their sides, and presence of parallel or perpendicular lines.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u8_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U8-L3",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 8 Lesson 3: Ways to Look at Quadrilaterals. The purpose of this lesson is for students to classify quadrilaterals by the size of their angles, the length of their sides, and the presence of parallel and perpendicular sides. Goals: Describe (orally and in writing) the attributes of squares, rectangles, parallelograms, and rhombuses. | Match (orally and in writing) quadrilaterals based on the length of their sides, size of their angles, and presence of parallel or perpendicular sides.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u8_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U8-L4",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 8 Lesson 4: Symmetry in Figures (Part 1). The purpose of this lesson is to introduce the concept of line symmetry and for students to identify lines of symmetry in two-dimensional figures. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the term “line of symmetry.\" | Explain (orally and in writing) how to determine if a figure has 1 or more lines of symmetry.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u8_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U8-L5",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 8 Lesson 5: Symmetry in Figures (Part 2). The purpose of this lesson is for students to identify figures with line symmetry and to complete line-symmetric figures. Goals: Critique (orally and writing) drawings of figures that claim to have line symmetry. | Draw figures with line symmetry given half of the figure and a line of symmetry.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u8_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U8-L6",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 8 Lesson 6: All Kinds of Attributes. The purpose of this optional lesson is for students to use what they know about symmetry and parallel and perpendicular lines to complete or draw figures with those attributes on a grid. Goals: Draw figures with specified attributes, including lines of symmetry and presence of parallel or perpendicular sides.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u8_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U8-L7",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 8 Lesson 7: Ways to Find Unknown Length (Part 1). The purpose of this lesson is for students to use the known attributes of two-dimensional figures (such as side lengths and symmetry) to reason about the perimeter of shapes. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) expressions used to determine the perimeter of a two-dimensional shape. | Explain (orally) how to determine a perimeter of a figure with unknown side lengths using its properties.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u8_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U8-L8",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 8 Lesson 8: Ways to Find Unknown Length (Part 2). The purpose of this lesson is for students to use the attributes of two-dimensional figures (such as perimeter and symmetry) to reason about side lengths. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for determining an unknown side length for a two-dimensional figure given the perimeter and lines of symmetry.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u8_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U8-L9",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 8 Lesson 9: Symmetry in Action. The purpose of this optional lesson is for students to practice visualizing and drawing figures given lines of symmetry and to use symmetry to solve problems about side lengths and perimeter. Goals: Solve problems involving symmetry, side lengths, and perimeter of two-dimensional figures.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u8_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U8-L10",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 8 Lesson 10: Ways to Find Angle Measurements. The purpose of this optional lesson is for students to use the attributes of figures (symmetry, equal side lengths, right angles) to reason about angle measurements. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for determining an unknown angle measurement using the attributes of two-dimensional figures.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u8_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U8-L11",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 8 Lesson 11: Symmetry in Sports. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply what they have learned about symmetry to the design of sports fields and rules of play. Goals: Present (orally and using other representations) the effects of removing symmetry from a sports field on its rules of play.").
%   Unit 9
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u9_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U9-L1",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 9 Lesson 1: Add, Subtract, and Multiply Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent and solve problems involving fraction operations. Students also reason about equivalence to compare fractions to whole numbers. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for comparing fractions. | Use addition, subtraction, and multiplication equations to represent and solve problems involving fractions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u9_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U9-L2",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 9 Lesson 2: Sums and Differences of Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent and solve problems involving the addition and subtraction of fractions. Students also reason about equivalence to compare fractions and make sense of problems. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for solving problems involving addition and subtraction of fractions and mixed numbers with like denominators.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u9_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U9-L3",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 9 Lesson 3: Stories with Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is to use understanding of equivalence to solve addition and subtraction problems with decimal fractions. Students also create their own word problems that involve the addition and subtraction of fractions. Goals: Create (in writing) word problems that represent a given sum, difference, or equation with an unknown value. | Explain (orally) strategies for solving problems involving adding, subtracting, and comparing decimal fractions.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u9_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U9-L4",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 9 Lesson 4: Another Look at the Standard Algorithm. The purpose of this lesson is to practice the standard algorithm for subtraction and to compare this method to other methods. Students choose a subtraction method, based on the relationship between the numbers in the expression, and explain Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) different strategies for subtracting multi-digit numbers. | Use the standard algorithm to subtract multi-digit numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u9_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U9-L5",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 9 Lesson 5: Multiplication of Multi-digit Numbers. The purpose of this lesson is to deepen students’ understanding of the connections between algorithms that use partial products and the standard algorithm when multiplying a pair of two-digit numbers. Goals: Interpet (orally and in writing) recording methods for multiplying multi-digit numbers. | Use strategies based on place value and the properties of operations to multiply multi-digit numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u9_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U9-L6",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 9 Lesson 6: What’s the Quotient?. The purpose of this lesson is to reinforce students’ understanding of division algorithms that use partial quotients and build their fluency in using it to divide multi-digit numbers by a single-digit divisor. Students also consider differe Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for dividing up to four-digit numbers by single-digit numbers. | Interpret (orally and in writing) strategies for dividing up to four-digit numbers by single-digit numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u9_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U9-L7",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 9 Lesson 7: Solve Multiplicative Comparison Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve problems involving multiplicative comparison. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for solving multi-step problems involving multiplicative comparison.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u9_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U9-L8",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 9 Lesson 8: Solve Problems with Multiplication and Division. The purpose of this lesson is for students to practice solving multi-step problems, using all operations. Students interpret their solutions (including remainders in division situations) and determine the reasonableness of their answer for  Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for solving problems involving division and interpreting remainders. | Justify (orally) that a solution to a problem involving division of whole numbers is reasonable.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u9_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U9-L9",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 9 Lesson 9: Create Word Problems. The purpose of this lesson is for students to create their own mathematical questions and word problems given constraints (specific values, possible operations). Goals: Create (in writing) word problems, including multi- step problems, that represent a given number and that use given operations.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u9_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U9-L10",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 9 Lesson 10: Estimation Exploration. The purpose of this lesson is for students to analyze different kinds of estimation problems and ways to make estimates, and then to write their own estimation problems. Goals: Create (in writing) and present an Estimation Exploration activity. | Explain (orally) strategies for estimating problems involving multiplication of multi-digit numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u9_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U9-L11",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 9 Lesson 11: Which Three Go Together. The purpose of this lesson is for students to analyze numbers, expressions, or geometric figures in order to identify shared features and unique features, and then to use their analyses to complete and create a Which Three Go Together? Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) numbers, expressions, and geometric figures. | Create (in writing) a Which Three Go Together?").
standard_anchor(im_grade4_u9_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G4-U9-L12",
    "IM Grade4 Unit 9 Lesson 12: Number Talk. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use patterns, structure, and understanding of the properties of operations to design a series of expressions for a Number Talk. Goals: Create a Number Talk activity. | Describe (orally) how a set of expressions are related.").
% ─ grade5 ─
%   Unit 1
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u1_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U1-L1",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 1 Lesson 1: What Is Volume?. The purpose of this lesson is for students to understand that solid objects have measurable attributes. One of these attributes is volume, which is defined as the amount of space taken up by an object. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) measurable attributes of solid objects. | Comprehend (in spoken and written language) the meaning of the term “volume.”").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u1_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U1-L2",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 1 Lesson 2: Measure Volume. The purpose of this lesson is for students to understand that volume is the amount of unit cubes that fills a space. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken language) the meaning of the term “unit cube.” | Describe (orally) attributes of rectangular prisms composed of connecting cubes. | Explain (orally) strategies for determining the volume of a solid object composed of unit cubes.").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u1_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U1-L3",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 1 Lesson 3: Volume of Prism Drawings. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find the volume of a rectangular prism, using its layered structure. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for calculating the volume of a rectangular prism composed of unit cubes.").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u1_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U1-L4",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 1 Lesson 4: Use Layers to Determine Volume. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply their understanding of the layered structure of rectangular prisms to find the volume of a prism when they cannot see all of the cubes. Goals: Generalize (orally and in writing) that the volume of a rectangular prism composed of unit cubes is the product of the number of cubes in one layer and the total number of layers. | Interpret (orally and in writing) a multiplication expression that represents the volume of a rect").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u1_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U1-L5",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 1 Lesson 5: Side Lengths of Rectangular Prisms. The purpose of this lesson is for students to formalize the language they use to describe the side lengths of a rectangular prism. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) that a “base” of a rectangular prism is a face of the prism. | Describe (orally) how a multiplication expression represents the volume of a rectangular prism composed of unit cubes. | Determine the volume of a rectangular prism, given a").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u1_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U1-L6",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 1 Lesson 6: Expressions for Volume. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use their understanding of the structure of a rectangular prism to find volume and write numerical expressions to represent volume. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) different ways of determining the volume of a rectangular prism. | Comprehend (in spoken and written language) that the “length, the width, and the height” of a rectangular prism refer to the side lengths of the prism. | Match (orally) rectangular pr").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u1_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U1-L7",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 1 Lesson 7: Cubic Units of Measure. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find the volume of rectangular prisms in cubic centimeters, cubic inches, and cubic feet. Goals: Comprehend (in spoken and written language) that a “cubic unit” is the volume of a cube of side length 1 unit. | Determine the information needed to find the volume of a rectangular prism. Ask (orally) questions to elicit that information. | Identify appropriate standard units of").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u1_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U1-L8",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 1 Lesson 8: Figures Made of Prisms. The purpose of this lesson is for students to recognize the structure of a solid figure made up of two non-overlapping right rectangular prisms and understand that its volume is the sum of the volumes of the two rectangular prisms. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for calculating the volume of a figure composed of rectangular prisms, with visible unit cubes.").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u1_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U1-L9",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 1 Lesson 9: Measure Figures Made from Prisms. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find the volume of a figure composed of two non-overlapping right rectangular prisms by adding the volumes of the non-overlapping parts. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for calculating the volume of a figure composed of rectangular prisms in which unit cubes are not visible. | Interpret (orally and in writing) an expression that represents the volume of a figure composed of rectangular prisms.").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u1_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U1-L10",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 1 Lesson 10: Represent Volume with Expressions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to write, interpret, and evaluate numerical expressions that represent the volumes of solid figures composed of two right rectangular prisms. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally and in writing) expressions that represent the volume of a figure composed of rectangular prisms. | Determine the volume of a figure composed of rectangular prisms and represent it with an expression.").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u1_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U1-L11",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 1 Lesson 11: All Kinds of Prisms. The mathematical purpose of this lesson is for students to apply what they have learned about finding the volumes of right rectangular prisms, and figures composed of right rectangular prisms, to solve real-world problems. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for finding the volumes of figures in real-world and mathematical problems.").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u1_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U1-L12",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 1 Lesson 12: Tons and Tons of Garbage. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use their understanding of the volume of rectangular prisms to solve a real- world problem. Goals: Determine an estimate for volume in a real-world problem, and justify (orally and in writing) the estimate. | Generate different figures composed of rectangular prisms with a given volume.").
%   Unit 2
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u2_l1, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U2-L1",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 2 Lesson 1: Share Sandwiches. The purpose of this lesson is for students to relate equal shares of objects to division and to fractions. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) a strategy for solving a whole-number division story problem with a solution that is a fraction. | Interpret (orally and in writing) a diagram that represents a whole-number division story problem with a solution that is a fraction.").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u2_l2, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U2-L2",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 2 Lesson 2: Share More Sandwiches. The purpose of this lesson is for students to relate equal shares to division expressions and visual representations of fractions. Goals: Match (orally) diagrams, division expressions, and fractions that represent the same situation. | Use a whole-number division expression to represent a story problem with a solution that is a fraction.").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u2_l3, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U2-L3",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 2 Lesson 3: Interpret Equations. The purpose of this lesson is for students to write equations to represent division situations and relate each part of the equation to the situation. Goals: Generalize (orally and in writing) that if     and    are whole numbers, then                . | Use a division equation to represent a whole-number division story problem with a solution that is a fraction.").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u2_l4, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U2-L4",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 2 Lesson 4: Division Situations. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve division problems when the quotient is a fraction or mixed number. Goals: Create and match (orally and in writing) diagrams, equations, and story problems that represent a whole-number division problem with a solution that is a fraction. | Explain (orally and in writing) a strategy for solving an unknown-factor, whole-number division story problem with").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u2_l5, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U2-L5",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 2 Lesson 5: Relate Division and Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to explain why           and apply their understanding to flexibly interpret division situations and equations where the unknown is the numerator, denominator, or the value of the quotient. Goals: Justify (orally and using words or other representations) that if and are whole numbers, then").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u2_l6, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U2-L6",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 2 Lesson 6: Relate Division and Multiplication. The purpose of this lesson is for students to understand that dividing an amount into a whole number of equal parts can be interpreted as multiplying the same amount by a unit fraction. Goals: Describe (orally) how equivalent multiplication and division expressions can represent the same diagram. | Use a diagram to represent a whole-number division story problem with a rational solution.").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u2_l7, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U2-L7",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 2 Lesson 7: Divide to Multiply Unit Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to solve problems involving multiplication of whole numbers by unit fractions and represent the problems with equations and diagrams. Goals: Compare and contrast (orally) strategies used to solve a story problem that can be represented as a product of a whole number and a unit fraction. | Match (orally) diagrams, multiplication expressions, and division expressions that represent the same situation.").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u2_l8, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U2-L8",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 2 Lesson 8: Divide to Multiply Non-Unit Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to represent and solve problems involving a non-unit fraction. Goals: Describe (orally and in writing) how a fraction and different, equivalent expressions, represent the same diagram. | Explain (orally and in writing) a strategy for determining the product of a whole number and a fraction.").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u2_l9, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U2-L9",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 2 Lesson 9: Relate Area to Multiplication. The purpose of this lesson is for students to calculate the area of a rectangle whose side lengths are a unit fraction and a whole number in a way that makes sense to them. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) a strategy for determining the area of a rectangle with a whole- number side length and a unit fraction side length.").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u2_l10, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U2-L10",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 2 Lesson 10: Fractional Side Lengths Less than 1. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find the area of rectangles with one non-unit fractional side length and one whole number side length. Goals: Determine the area of a rectangle with a whole- number side length and a rational side length less than 1 and represent it with a multiplication expression.").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u2_l11, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U2-L11",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 2 Lesson 11: Fractional Side Lengths Greater than 1. The purpose of this lesson is for students to find the area of a rectangle when one of the side lengths is a fraction greater than 1. Goals: Describe (orally and in writing) how different, equivalent multiplication expressions represent the area of a given rectangle with fractional side lengths greater than 1. | Explain (orally) strategies used to determine the area of a rectangle with fractional side lengths and repr").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u2_l12, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U2-L12",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 2 Lesson 12: Decompose Area. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply what they know about multiplication of whole numbers and fractions to decompose a rectangle to find its area. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for determining the area of a rectangle with fractional side lengths greater than 1 by decomposing it. | Interpret (orally and using words or other representations) the area of a rectangle that includes a fractional side length expressed as a mixed num").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u2_l13, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U2-L13",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 2 Lesson 13: Area and Properties of Operations. The purpose of this lesson is for students to analyze area diagrams and use the properties of operations to represent the area of rectangles. Goals: Generate (in writing) expressions that represent the area of a rectangle with fractional side lengths greater than 1. | Identify (orally and in writing) different numerical expressions that represent the same area of a rectangle with fractional side lengths greater than 1.").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u2_l14, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U2-L14",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 2 Lesson 14: Area Situations. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply their understanding of multiplying a whole number by a fraction to solve mathematical and real-world problems. Goals: Determine what information is needed to solve a multi-step area problem involving multiplication of a whole number and a fraction. Ask (orally) questions to elicit that information.").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u2_l15, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U2-L15",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 2 Lesson 15: Multiply More Fractions. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply their understanding of the properties of operations to multiply whole numbers and fractions greater than 1 written as mixed numbers. Goals: Explain (orally) strategies for determining unknown factors or products in area contexts that involve a mixed number. | Match (orally and in writing) diagrams and expressions that represent the same way to calculate the product of a whole-number and a fraction.").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u2_l16, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U2-L16",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 2 Lesson 16: Estimate Products. The purpose of this lesson is for students to reason about the value of the product of a whole number and a fraction greater than 1 and use the properties of operations to find the product. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for determining whole-number estimates to products of mixed numbers.").
standard_anchor(im_grade5_u2_l17, im_lesson, "IM-G5-U2-L17",
    "IM Grade5 Unit 2 Lesson 17: Mosaic Pictures. The purpose of this lesson is for students to use multiplication of fractions to create and analyze a mosaic of rectangles. Goals: Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for solving real-world area problems involving multiplication of whole numbers and fractions.").
